{"title_page": "Elisha Cook Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{distinguish|Elisha Cooke Jr.}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Elisha Cook Jr.\n| image         = Elisha Cook, Jr.jpg\n| caption       = Cook in ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956)\n| birth_name    = Elisha Vanslyck Cook Jr.\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1903|12|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], California, U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1995|5|18|1903|12|26}}\n| death_place   = [[Big Pine, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| residence     = Big Pine, California, U.S.\n| home_town     = [[Chicago]], Illinois\n| years_active  = 1926&ndash;1988\n| occupation    = Actor\n| spouse        = Mary Gertrude Dunckley (m. 1928; div. 1941)<br>Elvira A. (Peggy) McKenna (m. 1943; div. 1968)<br>Elvira A. (Peggy) McKenna (m. 1971; her death 1990)\n\n}}\n\n'''Elisha Vanslyck Cook Jr.''' (December 26, 1903&nbsp;\u2013 May 18, 1995) was an American stage, film and television [[character actor]] who often specialized in roles as \"cowardly villains and neurotics\".<ref name=\"TCM\">[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/38491|46419/Elisha-Cook-Jr/biography.html \"Elisha Cook, Jr. Biography\"], Turner Classic Movies (TCM), Turner Broadcasting System, a subsidiary of [[Time Warner, Inc.]], New York City, New York.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>  He is perhaps best remembered for his portrayal of Wilmer in the 1941 version of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' and the futile efforts made by his character to intimidate [[Sam Spade]] ([[Humphrey Bogart]]) in the film.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Thomas Jr.|first=Robert McG.|authorlink=Robert McG. Thomas|title=Elisha Cook Jr., Villain in Many Films, Dies at 91.|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=Elisha Cook Jr., whose intense, bug-eyed portrayal of Wilmer, the psychotic, baby-faced killer in The Maltese Falcon, made him a cult figure to a generation of moviegoers, died on Thursday at a nursing home in [[Big Pine, California]]. He was 91. He was the last surviving cast member of John Huston's 1941 film noir classic, whose company included Humphrey Bogart, Sydney Greenstreet, Peter Lorre and Mary Astor.|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE5D91531F932A15756C0A963958260|date=May 21, 1995}}</ref>  Cook's acting career spanned more than 60 years, with roles in productions including ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'', ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'', ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'', ''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'', and ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]''.\n\n==Early life, stage, and military service==\n[[File:Ah-Wilderness-1933.jpg|thumb|left|Around the table in the [[Theatre Guild]]'s original 1933 Broadway production of ''[[Ah, Wilderness!]]'' are (from left) [[George M. Cohan]], Eda Heinemann, Elisha Cook, Jr., [[Gene Lockhart]], Marjorie Marquis, Walter Vonnegut, Jr. and Adelaide Bean.]]\nCook was born in 1903 in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], the son of Elisha Vanslyck Cook Sr., a pharmacist, and grew up in [[Chicago]].  He first worked in theater lobbies selling programs, but by the age of 14 he was already performing in [[vaudeville]] and [[Summer stock theatre|stock]].<ref>Folkart, Burt A. (1995).  [https://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-20/news/mn-3760_1_elisha-cook-jr \"Elisha Cook Jr., 91; Classic Movie Villain\",] ''Los Angeles Times,'' May 20, 1995.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>   As a young man, he traveled and honed his acting skills on stages along the East Coast and in the Midwest before arriving in [[New York City]], where in 1926 he debuted on [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] in ''Hello, Lola.''<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0176879/otherworks?ref_=nm_pdt_wrk_sm  \"Elisha Cook Jr.: Other Works\"] Internet Movie Database ([[IMDb]]), a subsidiary of [[Amazon.com|Amazon]], Seattle Washington.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>   Some other Broadway productions in which Cook performed were ''Henry-Behave'' (1926), ''Kingdom of God'' (1928), ''Her Unborn Child'' (1928), ''Many a Slip'' (1930), ''Privilege Car'' (1931), ''Lost Boy'' (1932), ''Merry-Go-Round'' (1932), and ''Chrysalis'' (1932).<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\"/>   Then, in 1933, [[Eugene O'Neill]] cast him in the role of Richard Miller in his play ''[[Ah, Wilderness]],'' which ran on Broadway for two years.<ref name=NYT/>  Cook continued to appear on stage during the remainder the 1930s; and although his acting career after that focused increasingly on films and then on television roles, he periodically returned to Broadway, where as late as 1963 he performed as Giuseppe Givola in [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s play ''[[The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui]].''<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\"/>\n\nCook enlisted in the [[United States Army]] in Los Angeles, California, on August 15, 1942.<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\">[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:K853-KKZ \"United States World War II Army Enlistment Records, 1938-1946:  Cook Jr, Elisha V.], enlistment date 15 August 1942, Los Angeles, California, United States; merged database with \"Electronic Army Serial Number Merged File, ''ca.'' 1938-1946,\" Access to Archival Databases (AAD), National Archives and Records Administration (2002), National Archives, College Park, Maryland.  Transcription of noted enlistment record available at [[FamilySearch]], a free online genealogical database provided as a public service by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Salt Lake City, Utah.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>  According to his enlistment record he stood 5-feet-5-inches tall and weighed 123 pounds.<ref>WWII US Army Enlistment Records, 1938-46</ref>  Cook's military record also documents that his highest level of education by that time was his completion of \"3 years of high school.\"<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\"/>  Many online references, however, state that he had attended \"St. Albans College,\" \"The Chicago Academy of Dramatic Art,\" and \"The Chicago Academy of Fine Arts,\" which had been renamed the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] in 1882.  Those same references, though, do not provide any dates when Cook reportedly took classes at or graduated from those cited institutions.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/525/000174003/ Notable Names Database] [[NNDB]], Soylent Communications, Mountain View, California, 2016.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Career in film==\nIn 1930, Cook traveled to California, where he made his film debut in [[Hollywood]]'s version of the play ''Her Unborn Child'', a motion picture directed by [[Albert Ray]] and produced by Windsor Picture Plays Inc.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/495672/Her-Unborn-Child/ \"Her Unborn Child (1930)\"], Turner Classic Movies (TCM), Turner Broadcasting System, a subsidiary of Time Warner, Inc., New York City, New York.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>  After several subsequent small roles and uncredited parts in other films, he began a long period playing weaklings or sadistic losers and hoodlums, who in the plots were usually murdered, either being strangled, poisoned or shot. Hollywood's most established [[fall guy]] for many years, he made a rare appearance in a cameo role in the 1941 slapstick comedy ''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'', performing as a [[screenwriter]].  In [[Universal Pictures|Universal]]'s ''[[Phantom Lady (1944)|Phantom Lady]]'' (1944), he portrays a slimy, intoxicated nightclub-orchestra drummer to memorable effect. He also had a substantial, though uncredited role as Bobo in the 1953 [[film noir]] production ''[[I, the Jury (1953 film)|I, the Jury]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n[[File:WilmerMaltFalc1941Trailer.jpg|thumb|left|Cook in ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941)]]\n[[File:Tierney and Cook in Born to Kill.jpg|right|thumb|Cook meeting a typical sticky end at the hands of [[Lawrence Tierney]] in ''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947)]]\nIn addition to his performance as Wilmer in ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941), some of Cook's other notable roles include the doomed informant Harry Jones in ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'' (1946), the henchman (Marty Waterman) of the murderous title character in ''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947), the pugnacious ex-Confederate soldier 'Stonewall' Torrey who is gunned down by Jack Palance in ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'' (1953), and George Peatty, the shady, cuckolded husband in [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956).  Other films in which he appeared are [[William Castle]]'s horror film ''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'' (1959), ''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961), ''[[Papa's Delicate Condition]]'' (1963), ''[[Blood on the Arrow]]'' (1964), ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' (1968), ''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' (1969), ''[[El Condor (film)|El Condor]]'' (1970), ''[[The Great Northfield Minnesota Raid]]'' (1972), ''[[Pat Garrett and Billy the Kid]]'' (1973), ''[[The Outfit (1973 film)|The Outfit]]'' (1973), ''[[Tom Horn]]'' (1980), and ''[[Treasure: In Search of the Golden Horse]]'' (1984).<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Television==\nCook appeared on a wide variety of American television series from the early 1950s to the late 1980s.  He played a private detective, Homer Garrity, in an episode of ''[[Adventures of Superman (TV series)|Adventures of Superman]]'' [[television series]] titled \"Semi-Private Eye,\" airing for the first time on January 16, 1954. That same year, on April 12, he guest-starred on [[NBC]]'s ''[[The Dennis Day Show]].''  In 1960, he was cast in the episode \"The Hermit\" of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[The Real McCoys]]'' with [[Walter Brennan]]. He appeared too in 1960 as Jeremy Hake in the episode \"The Bequest\" of the ABC western series ''[[The Rebel (TV series)|The Rebel]]'', which starred [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]]. He also portrayed the character Gideon McCoy in the 1966 episode \"The Night of the Bars of Hell\" on ''[[The Wild Wild West]]''. He performed as well in the second episode of ABC's crime drama ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]''.\n\nCook made two guest appearances on the [[CBS]] courtroom drama series ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]''.  In 1958, he played Art Crowley in \"The Case of the Pint-Sized Client\", and in 1964 he played Reelin' Peter Rockwell in \"The Case of the Reckless Rockhound\". Cook portrayed lawyer Samuel T. Cogley in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' 1967 episode \"[[Court Martial (TOS episode)|Court Martial]]\", Isaac Isaacson on the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' television series, Weasel Craig in ''[[Salem's Lot (1979 TV mini-series)|Salem's Lot]]'', and later had a long-term recurring role as [[Honolulu]] crime lord \"Ice Pick\" on CBS's ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]''   He appeared too in ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' episode \"Once a Thief\" in 1977.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|176879}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of his life, Cook often played dim witted or cranky elderly characters.  He played a bum in an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]'' as well as an elderly uncle in an episode of ''[[ALF (TV series)|Alf]]'', which was one of his last roles prior to his retirement entirely from acting in 1988, followed by his death seven years later.\n\n==Personal life==\nElisha Cook was officially married three times, the first time to singer Mary Gertrude (''n\u00e9e'' Dunckley) Cook (1910-1944) from 1928 until their divorce on November 4, 1941.<ref>Long Beach Independent; May 30, 1944; Page 10; Find Liver Ailment Causes Singers Death</ref>  He then married Illinois native Elvira Ann (Peggy) McKenna in 1943.  The couple were married for 25 years until they formally divorced in [[Inyo County, California]], in February 1968.  Peggy and Elisha, however, remarried just short of four years later, on December 30, 1971.<ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPRR-JRW \"California Divorce Index, 1966-1984\"], divorce of Elvira A. McKenna and Elisha V. Cook, February, 1968, Inyo County, California.  California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, CA.  Transcribed document available on FamilySearch, a free online genealogical database provided as a free public service by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Salt Lake City, Utah.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"imdb\"/>  Their second marriage lasted another 19 years, until Peggy's death on December 23, 1990. Various references about Cook state that he had no children from his marriages; yet, his army enlistment record of 1942 documents his marital status as \"Divorced, with dependents,\" which suggests he may have had a child or children with his first wife.<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\"/>  He resided for many years in [[Bishop, California|Bishop]], although he typically spent his summers at [[Lake Sabrina]] in the Sierra Nevada.<ref name=NYT/>  According to [[John Huston]], who in 1941 directed him in ''The Maltese Falcon'':\n<blockquote>\n[Cook] lived alone up in the High Sierra, tied flies and caught golden trout between films. When he was wanted in Hollywood, they sent word up to his mountain cabin by courier. He would come down, do a picture, and then withdraw again to his retreat.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Huston|first=John|authorlink=John Huston|title=An Open Book|isbn=978-0-306-80573-8|year=1994|publisher=Da Capo Press|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pqbsPJlscyYC&pg=PA79&dq=%22Elisha%20Cook,%20Jr.%22}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Death==\nCook died of a [[stroke]] at age 91, on May 18, 1995, at a [[Nursing home care|nursing home]] in [[Big Pine, California]].  He was the last surviving member of the main cast of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]''.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n==Complete filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''Her Unborn Child'' (1930) as Stewart Kennedy (film debut)\n*''Chills and Fever'' (1930 short) as Member of the Glee Club (uncredited)\n*''[[Honor Among Lovers]]'' (1931) as Office Boy (uncredited)\n*''[[Two in a Crowd]]'' (1936) as Skeeter\n*''[[Pigskin Parade]]'' (1936) as Herbert Van Dyke\n*''[[Breezing Home]]'' (1937) as Pete Espinosa (uncredited)\n*''[[Love Is News]]'' (1937) as Egbert Eggleston\n*''[[The Devil Is Driving (1937 film)|The Devil Is Driving]]'' (1937) as Tony Stevens\n*''[[They Won't Forget]]'' (1937) as Joe Turner\n*''[[Wife, Doctor and Nurse]]'' (1937) as Glen Wylie\n*''[[Danger - Love at Work]]'' (1937) as Chemist\n*''[[Life Begins in College]]'' (1937) as Ollie Stearns\n*''[[Thoroughbreds Don't Cry]]'' (1937) as Boots Maguire (uncredited)\n*''[[Three Blind Mice (1938 film)|Three Blind Mice]]'' (1938) as Boy on Bench (uncredited)\n*''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]'' (1938) as Waldo\n*''[[Submarine Patrol]]'' (1938) as Seaman Rutherford Davis Pratt, aka 'The Professor'\n*''[[Newsboys' Home]]'' (1938) as Danny\n*''[[Grand Jury Secrets]]'' (1939) as Robert Austin / Norman Hazlitt\n*''[[He Married His Wife]]'' (1940) as Dicky Brown\n*''[[Stranger on the Third Floor]]'' (1940) as Joe Briggs\n*''[[Public Deb No. 1]]'' (1940) as Communist\n*''[[Tin Pan Alley (film)|Tin Pan Alley]]'' (1940) as Joe Codd\n*''[[Love Crazy (1941 film)|Love Crazy]]'' (1941) as Elevator Man\n*''[[Sergeant York (film)|Sergeant York]]'' (1941) as Piano Player (uncredited)\n*''[[Man at Large]]'' (1941) as Hotel Clerk\n*''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941) as Wilmer Cook\n*''[[I Wake Up Screaming]]'' (1941) as Harry Williams\n*''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'' (1941) as Harry Selby\n*''[[Ball of Fire]]'' (1941) as Waiter\n*''[[A Gentleman at Heart]]'' (1942) as Genius\n*''[[Sleepytime Gal]]'' (1942) as Ernie\n*''[[A-Haunting We Will Go (1942 film)|A-Haunting We Will Go]]'' (1942) as Frank Lucas\n*''[[Wildcat (film)|Wildcat]]'' (1942) as Harold 'Chicopee' Nevins\n*''[[Manila Calling]]'' (1942) as Gillman\n*''[[Kill or Be Killed (1942 film)|Kill or Be Killed]]'' (1942)\n*''[[Baptism of Fire]]'' (1943 documentary) as Bill\n*''[[Phantom Lady (film)|Phantom Lady]]'' (1944) as Cliff\n*''[[Up in Arms]]'' (1944) as Info Jones\n*''[[Dark Mountain (film)|Dark Mountain]]'' (1944) as Whitey\n*''[[Dark Waters (1944 film)|Dark Waters]]'' (1944) as Cleeve\n*''[[Dillinger (1945 film)|Dillinger]]'' (1945) as Kirk Otto\n*''[[Why Girls Leave Home (1945 film)|Why Girls Leave Home]]'' (1945) as Jimmy Lobo\n*''[[Blonde Alibi]]'' (1946) as Sam Collins\n*''[[Cinderella Jones]]'' (1946) as Oliver S. Patch\n*''[[The Falcon's Alibi]]'' (1946) as Nick\n*''[[Joe Palooka, Champ]]'' (1946) as Eugene\n*''[[Two Smart People]]'' (1946) as Fly Feletti\n*''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'' (1946) as Harry Jones\n*''[[Fall Guy (1947 film)|Fall Guy]]'' (1947) as Joe\n*''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947) as Marty\n*''[[The Long Night (1947 film)|The Long Night]]'' (1947) as Frank Dunlap\n*''[[The Gangster (1947 film)|The Gangster]]'' (1947) as Oval\n*''[[Flaxy Martin]]'' (1949) as Roper\n*''[[The Great Gatsby (1949 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (1949) as Klipspringer\n*''[[Behave Yourself!|Behave Yourself]]'' (1951) as Albert Jonas\n*''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) as Eddie Forbes\n*''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'' (1953) as Stonewall Torrey\n*''[[I, The Jury]]'' (1953) as Bobo (uncredited)\n*''[[Thunder Over the Plains]]'' (1953) as Joseph Standish\n*''[[The Outlaw's Daughter (film)|The Outlaw's Daughter]]'' (1954) as Lewis 'Tulsa' Cook\n*''[[Drum Beat]]'' (1954) as Blaine Crackel\n*''[[Timberjack (film)|Timberjack]]'' (1955) as Punky\n*''[[Trial (1955 film)|Trial]]'' (1955) as Finn\n*''[[The Indian Fighter]]'' (1955) as Briggs\n*''Indian Agent'' (1955, TV Movie) as Pete, the Cavalry Scout (uncredited)\n*''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956) as George Peatty\n*''[[Accused of Murder]]'' (1956) as \"Whitey\" Pollock\n*''[[Voodoo Island]]'' (1957) as Martin Schuyler\n*''[[The Lonely Man]]'' (1957) as Willie \n*''[[Chicago Confidential]]'' (1957) as Candymouth Duggan\n*''[[Plunder Road]]'' (1957) as Skeets Jonas\n*''[[Baby Face Nelson (film)|Baby Face Nelson]]'' (1957) as Homer van Meter\n*''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'' (1959) as Watson Pritchard \n*''[[Day of the Outlaw]]'' (1959) as Larry Teter (town barber)\n*''[[Platinum High School]]'' (1960) as Harry Nesbit\n*''[[College Confidential (film)|College Confidential]]'' (1960) as Ted Blake\n*''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961) as Carvey \n*''[[Papa's Delicate Condition]]'' (1963) as Mr. Keith\n*''[[Black Zoo]]'' (1963) as Joe\n*''[[The Haunted Palace]]'' (1963) as Peter Smith / Micah Smith \n*''[[Johnny Cool]]'' (1963) as Undertaker\n*''The Judge'' (1963, TV Movie) \n*''The Glass Cage'' (1964) as Girl's father\n*''[[Blood on the Arrow]]'' (1964) as Tex\n*''McNab's Lab'' (1966, TV Movie) as Coach\n*''[[The Spy in the Green Hat]]'' (1967) as Arnold\n*''[[Welcome to Hard Times (film)|Welcome to Hard Times]]'' (1967) as Hanson\n*''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' (1968) as Mr. Nicklas \n*''Cry for Poor Wally'' (1969) as Preacher\n*''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' (1969) as Jeb\n*''The Movie Murderer'' (1970, TV Movie) as Willie Peanuts\n*''[[El Condor (film)|El Condor]]'' (1970) as Old Convict\n*''Night Slaves'' (1970, TV Movie)\n*''Night Chase'' (1970, TV Movie) as Proprietor\n*''The Scarecrow'' (1972, TV Movie) as Micah\n*''[[The Night Stalker (1972 film)|The Night Stalker]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Mickey Crawford\n*''[[The Great Northfield Minnesota Raid]]'' (1972) as Bunker\n*''[[Blacula]]'' (1972) as Sam\n*''[[Messiah of Evil]]'' (1973) as Charlie\n*''[[Pat Garrett & Billy the Kid]]'' (1973) as Cody\n*''[[Emperor of the North Pole]]'' (1973) as Gray Cat \n*''[[Electra Glide in Blue]]'' (1973) as Willie\n*''[[The Outfit (1973 film)|The Outfit]]'' (1973) as Carl\n*''The Phantom of Hollywood'' (1974, TV Movie) as Studio Engineer (uncredited)\n*''[[Winterhawk]]'' (1975) as Finley\n*''[[The Black Bird]]'' (1975) as Wilmer Cook\n*''[[St. Ives (1976 film)|St. Ives]]'' (1976) as Eddie\n*''[[Dead of Night (1977 film)|Dead of Night]]'' (1977, TV Movie) as Karel\n*''Mad Bull'' (1977, TV Movie) as Sweeper\n*''[[The Champ (1979 film)|The Champ]]'' (1979) as Georgie \n*''[[Salem's Lot (1979 miniseries)|Salem's Lot]]'' (1979, TV Movie) as Gordon \"Weasel\" Phillips \n*''[[1941 (film)|1941]]'' (1979) as The Patron (Dexter)\n*''[[Tom Horn]]'' (1980) as Stablehand\n*''[[Carny (1980 film)|Carny]]'' (1980) as On-Your-Mark\n*''[[The Trouble with Grandpa]]'' (1981 TV movie) as Grampa\n*''[[Harry's War (1981 film)|Harry's War]]'' (1981) as Sgt. Billy\n*''Leave 'em Laughing'' (1981 TV movie) as Jetter\n*''[[National Lampoon's Movie Madness]]'' (1982) as Mousy (\"Municipalians\") \n*''[[Hammett (film)|Hammett]]'' (1982) as Eli the Taxi Driver\n*''Terror at Alcatraz'' (1982, TV Movie) as Hotel Desk Clerk\n*''This Girl for Hire'' (1983, TV Movie) as Eddie\n*''Shadow of Sam Penny'' (1983, TV Movie) as Dutch Silver\n*''[[Off Sides (Pigs vs. Freaks)]]'' (1984, TV Movie) as Novatney\n*''[[It Came Upon the Midnight Clear (film)|It Came Upon the Midnight Clear]]'' (1984, TV Movie) as Mr. Bibbs\n*''Treasure: In Search of the Golden Horse'' (1984) as Mr. Maps\n*''The Man Who Broke 1,000 Chains'' (1987, TV Movie) as Pappy Glue\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Television credits==\n{{div col|colwidth=26em}}\n*''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' in \"Salvage\" (1955) as Shorty\n*''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'' as \"Guns\" McCallum, a gunsmith with a hot temper hired by [[Dodge City, Kansas|Dodge City]] [[Mayor]] [[James H. Kelley|James H. \"Dog\" Kelley]] in \"The Equalizer\" (1957)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0631874/?ref_=tt_ep_ep16|title=The Equalizer'' on ''The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp''|date=April 16, 1957|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=April 16, 2014}}</ref>\n*''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'' in \"The Case of the Pint-Sized Client\" (1958) as Art Crowley\n*''[[Gunsmoke (TV series)|Gunsmoke]]'' in \"Matt for Murder\" (1958) as Huggins \n*''[[Gunsmoke (TV series)|Gunsmoke]]'' in \"Odd Man Out\" (1959) as Cyrus Tucker\n*''[[The Real McCoys]]'' in \"The Hermit\" (1960) as Harry\n*''[[Wagon Train]]'' in \"The Tracy Sadler Story\" (1960) as Cadge Waldo\n*''[[Tightrope (TV series)|Tightrope]]'' in \"The Long Odds\" (1960) as Sam Parker\n*''[[The Rebel (TV series)|The Rebel]]'' in \"The Bequest\" (1960) as Jeremy Hake\n*''[[Thriller (U.S. TV series)|Thriller]]'' in \"The Fatal Impulse\" (1960) as The Assassin\n*''[[The Islanders (TV series)|The Islanders]]'' in \"The Twenty-Six Paper\" (1961) as Tomas \n*''[[Surfside 6]]'' in \"Witness for the Defense\" (1961) as Mike Pulaski \n*''[[The Deputy (TV series)|The Deputy]]'' in \"Brand of Honesty\" (1961) as Miller\n*''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]'' in \"The Tumbleweed Wagon\" (1961) as Doc\n*''[[Outlaws (1960 TV series)|Outlaws]]'' in \"The Dark Sunrise of Griff Kincaid\" (1962) as Cully\n*''[[The Dakotas (TV series)|The Dakotas]]'' in \"A Nice Girl from Goliath\" (1963) as Brinkman\n*''[[Gunsmoke (TV series)|Gunsmoke]]'' in \"Hung High\" (1964) as George\n*''[[The Wild Wild West]]'' in \"The Night of the Bars of Hell\" (1966) as Gideon McCoy\n*''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' in \"Court Martial\" (1967) as Samuel T. Cogley, Esq \n*''[[The Odd Couple (1970 TV series)|The Odd Couple]]'' in \"Our Fathers\" (1974) as Eliot Ness\n*''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' in \"Once a Thief\" (1977) as Inky (credited as Elisha Cook)\n*''[[Magnum, P.I.]]'' (1980s) as Francis \"Ice Pick\" Hofstetler in 13 episodes (final television appearance)\n*''[[Night Court]]'' in \"Married Alive\" (1985) as Wilbur Posten\n*''[[The Twilight Zone (1985 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'' in \"[[Welcome to Winfield]]\" (1986) as Weldon\n*''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'' in \"We're So Sorry, Uncle Albert\" (1988) as Uncle Albert\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book \n|last= Young \n|first= Jordan R. \n|title= Reel Characters : Great Movie Character Actors \n|chapter= Elisha Cook Jr.\n|pages= 13-28\n|date= 1986 \n|edition= Sixth \n|orig-year=First published 1975 \n|type= softcover \n|publisher= Moonstone Press \n|location= Beverly Hills, CA \n|isbn = 978-0-940410-79-4}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{IMDb name|0176879}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n*{{Tcmdb name}}\n{{Memoryalpha}}\n*{{Find a Grave|6622584}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Theatre|Film|Television}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cook, Elisha Jr.}}\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{distinguish|Elisha Cooke Jr.}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Elisha Cook Jr.\n| image         = Elisha Cook, Jr.jpg\n| caption       = Cook in ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956)\n| birth_name    = Elisha Vanslyck Cook Jr.\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1903|12|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco]], California, U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1995|5|18|1903|12|26}}\n| death_place   = [[Big Pine, California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| residence     = Big Pine, California, U.S.\n| home_town     = [[Chicago]], Illinois\n| years_active  = 1926&ndash;1988\n| occupation    = Actor\n| spouse        = Mary Gertrude Dunckley (m. 1928; div. 1941)<br>Elvira A. (Peggy) McKenna (m. 1943; div. 1968)<br>Elvira A. (Peggy) McKenna (m. 1971; her death 1990)\n\n}}\n\n'''Elisha Vanslyck Cook Jr.''' (December 26, 1903&nbsp;\u2013 May 18, 1995) was an American stage, film and television [[character actor]] who often specialized in roles as \"cowardly villains and neurotics\".<ref name=\"TCM\">[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/38491|46419/Elisha-Cook-Jr/biography.html \"Elisha Cook, Jr. Biography\"], Turner Classic Movies (TCM), Turner Broadcasting System, a subsidiary of [[Time Warner, Inc.]], New York City, New York.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>  He is perhaps best remembered for his portrayal of Wilmer in the 1941 version of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' and the futile efforts made by his character to intimidate [[Sam Spade]] ([[Humphrey Bogart]]) in the film.<ref name=NYT>{{cite news|last=Thomas Jr.|first=Robert McG.|authorlink=Robert McG. Thomas|title=Elisha Cook Jr., Villain in Many Films, Dies at 91.|work=[[The New York Times]]|quote=Elisha Cook Jr., whose intense, bug-eyed portrayal of Wilmer, the psychotic, baby-faced killer in The Maltese Falcon, made him a cult figure to a generation of moviegoers, died on Thursday at a nursing home in [[Big Pine, California]]. He was 91. He was the last surviving cast member of John Huston's 1941 film noir classic, whose company included Humphrey Bogart, Sydney Greenstreet, Peter Lorre and Mary Astor.|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=990CE5D91531F932A15756C0A963958260|date=May 21, 1995}}</ref>  Cook's acting career spanned more than 60 years, with roles in productions including ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'', ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'', ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'', ''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'', and ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]''.\n\n==Early life, stage, and military service==\n[[File:Ah-Wilderness-1933.jpg|thumb|left|Around the table in the [[Theatre Guild]]'s original 1933 Broadway production of ''[[Ah, Wilderness!]]'' are (from left) [[George M. Cohan]], Eda Heinemann, Elisha Cook, Jr., [[Gene Lockhart]], Marjorie Marquis, Walter Vonnegut, Jr. and Adelaide Bean.]]\nCook was born in 1903 in [[San Francisco]], [[California]], the son of Elisha Vanslyck Cook Sr., a pharmacist, and grew up in [[Chicago]].  He first worked in theater lobbies selling programs, but by the age of 14 he was already performing in [[vaudeville]] and [[Summer stock theatre|stock]].<ref>Folkart, Burt A. (1995).  [https://articles.latimes.com/1995-05-20/news/mn-3760_1_elisha-cook-jr \"Elisha Cook Jr., 91; Classic Movie Villain\",] ''Los Angeles Times,'' May 20, 1995.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>   As a young man, he traveled and honed his acting skills on stages along the East Coast and in the Midwest before arriving in [[New York City]], where in 1926 he debuted on [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] in ''Hello, Lola.''<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\">[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0176879/otherworks?ref_=nm_pdt_wrk_sm  \"Elisha Cook Jr.: Other Works\"] Internet Movie Database ([[IMDb]]), a subsidiary of [[Amazon.com|Amazon]], Seattle Washington.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>   Some other Broadway productions in which Cook performed were ''Henry-Behave'' (1926), ''Kingdom of God'' (1928), ''Her Unborn Child'' (1928), ''Many a Slip'' (1930), ''Privilege Car'' (1931), ''Lost Boy'' (1932), ''Merry-Go-Round'' (1932), and ''Chrysalis'' (1932).<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\"/>   Then, in 1933, [[Eugene O'Neill]] cast him in the role of Richard Miller in his play ''[[Ah, Wilderness]],'' which ran on Broadway for two years.<ref name=NYT/>  Cook continued to appear on stage during the remainder the 1930s; and although his acting career after that focused increasingly on films and then on television roles, he periodically returned to Broadway, where as late as 1963 he performed as Giuseppe Givola in [[Bertolt Brecht]]'s play ''[[The Resistible Rise of Arturo Ui]].''<ref name=\"Cook IMDb\"/>\n\nCook enlisted in the [[United States Army]] in Los Angeles, California, on August 15, 1942.<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\">[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:K853-KKZ \"United States World War II Army Enlistment Records, 1938-1946:  Cook Jr, Elisha V.], enlistment date 15 August 1942, Los Angeles, California, United States; merged database with \"Electronic Army Serial Number Merged File, ''ca.'' 1938-1946,\" Access to Archival Databases (AAD), National Archives and Records Administration (2002), National Archives, College Park, Maryland.  Transcription of noted enlistment record available at [[FamilySearch]], a free online genealogical database provided as a public service by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Salt Lake City, Utah.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>  According to his enlistment record he stood 5-feet-5-inches tall and weighed 123 pounds.<ref>WWII US Army Enlistment Records, 1938-46</ref>  Cook's military record also documents that his highest level of education by that time was his completion of \"3 years of high school.\"<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\"/>  Many online references, however, state that he had attended \"St. Albans College,\" \"The Chicago Academy of Dramatic Art,\" and \"The Chicago Academy of Fine Arts,\" which had been renamed the [[Art Institute of Chicago]] in 1882.  Those same references, though, do not provide any dates when Cook reportedly took classes at or graduated from those cited institutions.<ref name=\"TCM\"/><ref>[http://www.nndb.com/people/525/000174003/ Notable Names Database] [[NNDB]], Soylent Communications, Mountain View, California, 2016.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref>\n\n==Career in film==\nIn 1930, Cook traveled to California, where he made his film debut in [[Hollywood]]'s version of the play ''Her Unborn Child'', a motion picture directed by [[Albert Ray]] and produced by Windsor Picture Plays Inc.<ref>[http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/495672/Her-Unborn-Child/ \"Her Unborn Child (1930)\"], Turner Classic Movies (TCM), Turner Broadcasting System, a subsidiary of Time Warner, Inc., New York City, New York.  Retrieved July 31, 2017.</ref>  After several subsequent small roles and uncredited parts in other films, he began a long period playing weaklings or sadistic losers and hoodlums, who in the plots were usually murdered, either being strangled, poisoned or shot. Hollywood's most established [[fall guy]] for many years, he made a rare appearance in a cameo role in the 1941 slapstick comedy ''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'', performing as a [[screenwriter]].  In [[Universal Pictures|Universal]]'s ''[[Phantom Lady (1944)|Phantom Lady]]'' (1944), he portrays a slimy, intoxicated nightclub-orchestra drummer to memorable effect. He also had a substantial, though uncredited role as Bobo in the 1953 [[film noir]] production ''[[I, the Jury (1953 film)|I, the Jury]]''.<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n[[File:WilmerMaltFalc1941Trailer.jpg|thumb|left|Cook in ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941)]]\n[[File:Tierney and Cook in Born to Kill.jpg|right|thumb|Cook meeting a typical sticky end at the hands of [[Lawrence Tierney]] in ''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947)]]\nIn addition to his performance as Wilmer in ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941), some of Cook's other notable roles include the doomed informant Harry Jones in ''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'' (1946), the henchman (Marty Waterman) of the murderous title character in ''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947), the pugnacious ex-Confederate soldier 'Stonewall' Torrey who is gunned down by Jack Palance in ''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'' (1953), and George Peatty, the shady, cuckolded husband in [[Stanley Kubrick]]'s ''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956).  Other films in which he appeared are [[William Castle]]'s horror film ''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'' (1959), ''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961), ''[[Papa's Delicate Condition]]'' (1963), ''[[Blood on the Arrow]]'' (1964), ''[[Rosemary's Baby (film)|Rosemary's Baby]]'' (1968), ''[[The Great Bank Robbery (1969 film)|The Great Bank Robbery]]'' (1969), ''[[El Condor (film)|El Condor]]'' (1970), ''[[The Great Northfield Minnesota Raid]]'' (1972), ''[[Pat Garrett and Billy the Kid]]'' (1973), ''[[The Outfit (1973 film)|The Outfit]]'' (1973), ''[[Tom Horn]]'' (1980), and ''[[Treasure: In Search of the Golden Horse]]'' (1984).<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n\n==Television==\nCook appeared on a wide variety of American television series from the early 1950s to the late 1980s.  He played a private detective, Homer Garrity, in an episode of ''[[Adventures of Superman (TV series)|Adventures of Superman]]'' [[television series]] titled \"Semi-Private Eye,\" airing for the first time on January 16, 1954. That same year, on April 12, he guest-starred on [[NBC]]'s ''[[The Dennis Day Show]].''  In 1960, he was cast in the episode \"The Hermit\" of the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[The Real McCoys]]'' with [[Walter Brennan]]. He appeared too in 1960 as Jeremy Hake in the episode \"The Bequest\" of the ABC western series ''[[The Rebel (TV series)|The Rebel]]'', which starred [[Nick Adams (actor, born 1931)|Nick Adams]]. He also portrayed the character Gideon McCoy in the 1966 episode \"The Night of the Bars of Hell\" on ''[[The Wild Wild West]]''. He performed as well in the second episode of ABC's crime drama ''[[The Fugitive (TV series)|The Fugitive]]''.\n\nCook made two guest appearances on the [[CBS]] courtroom drama series ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]''.  In 1958, he played Art Crowley in \"The Case of the Pint-Sized Client\", and in 1964 he played Reelin' Peter Rockwell in \"The Case of the Reckless Rockhound\". Cook portrayed lawyer Samuel T. Cogley in the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' 1967 episode \"[[Court Martial (TOS episode)|Court Martial]]\", Isaac Isaacson on the ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'' television series, Weasel Craig in ''[[Salem's Lot (1979 TV mini-series)|Salem's Lot]]'', and later had a long-term recurring role as [[Honolulu]] crime lord \"Ice Pick\" on CBS's ''[[Magnum, P.I.]]''   He appeared too in ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'' episode \"Once a Thief\" in 1977.<ref name=\"imdb\">{{IMDb name|176879}}</ref>\n\nTowards the end of his life, Cook often played dim witted or cranky elderly characters.  He played a bum in an episode of ''[[The A-Team]]'' as well as an elderly uncle in an episode of ''[[ALF (TV series)|Alf]]'', which was one of his last roles prior to his retirement entirely from acting in 1988, followed by his death seven years later.\n\n==Personal life==\nElisha Cook was officially married three times, the first time to singer Mary Gertrude (''n\u00e9e'' Dunckley) Cook (1910-1944) from 1928 until their divorce on November 4, 1941.<ref>Long Beach Independent; May 30, 1944; Page 10; Find Liver Ailment Causes Singers Death</ref>  He then married Illinois native Elvira Ann (Peggy) McKenna in 1943.  The couple were married for 25 years until they formally divorced in [[Inyo County, California]], in February 1968.  Peggy and Elisha, however, remarried just short of four years later, on December 30, 1971.<ref>[https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPRR-JRW \"California Divorce Index, 1966-1984\"], divorce of Elvira A. McKenna and Elisha V. Cook, February, 1968, Inyo County, California.  California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, CA.  Transcribed document available on FamilySearch, a free online genealogical database provided as a free public service by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, Salt Lake City, Utah.  Retrieved July 30, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"imdb\"/>  Their second marriage lasted another 19 years, until Peggy's death on December 23, 1990. Various references about Cook state that he had no children from his marriages; yet, his army enlistment record of 1942 documents his marital status as \"Divorced, with dependents,\" which suggests he may have had a child or children with his first wife.<ref name=\"Cook Military Record\"/>  He resided for many years in [[Bishop, California|Bishop]], although he typically spent his summers at [[Lake Sabrina]] in the Sierra Nevada.<ref name=NYT/>  According to [[John Huston]], who in 1941 directed him in ''The Maltese Falcon'':\n<blockquote>\n[Cook] lived alone up in the High Sierra, tied flies and caught golden trout between films. When he was wanted in Hollywood, they sent word up to his mountain cabin by courier. He would come down, do a picture, and then withdraw again to his retreat.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Huston|first=John|authorlink=John Huston|title=An Open Book|isbn=978-0-306-80573-8|year=1994|publisher=Da Capo Press|page=79|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pqbsPJlscyYC&pg=PA79&dq=%22Elisha%20Cook,%20Jr.%22}}</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Death==\nCook died of a [[stroke]] at age 91, on May 18, 1995, at a [[Nursing home care|nursing home]] in [[Big Pine, California]].  He was the last surviving member of the main cast of ''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]''.<ref name=NYT/>\n\n==Complete filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*''Her Unborn Child'' (1930) as Stewart Kennedy (film debut)\n*''Chills and Fever'' (1930 short) as Member of the Glee Club (uncredited)\n*''[[Honor Among Lovers]]'' (1931) as Office Boy (uncredited)\n*''[[Two in a Crowd]]'' (1936) as Skeeter\n*''[[Pigskin Parade]]'' (1936) as Herbert Van Dyke\n*''[[Breezing Home]]'' (1937) as Pete Espinosa (uncredited)\n*''[[Love Is News]]'' (1937) as Egbert Eggleston\n*''[[The Devil Is Driving (1937 film)|The Devil Is Driving]]'' (1937) as Tony Stevens\n*''[[They Won't Forget]]'' (1937) as Joe Turner\n*''[[Wife, Doctor and Nurse]]'' (1937) as Glen Wylie\n*''[[Danger - Love at Work]]'' (1937) as Chemist\n*''[[Life Begins in College]]'' (1937) as Ollie Stearns\n*''[[Thoroughbreds Don't Cry]]'' (1937) as Boots Maguire (uncredited)\n*''[[Three Blind Mice (1938 film)|Three Blind Mice]]'' (1938) as Boy on Bench (uncredited)\n*''[[My Lucky Star (1938 film)|My Lucky Star]]'' (1938) as Waldo\n*''[[Submarine Patrol]]'' (1938) as Seaman Rutherford Davis Pratt, aka 'The Professor'\n*''[[Newsboys' Home]]'' (1938) as Danny\n*''[[Grand Jury Secrets]]'' (1939) as Robert Austin / Norman Hazlitt\n*''[[He Married His Wife]]'' (1940) as Dicky Brown\n*''[[Stranger on the Third Floor]]'' (1940) as Joe Briggs\n*''[[Public Deb No. 1]]'' (1940) as Communist\n*''[[Tin Pan Alley (film)|Tin Pan Alley]]'' (1940) as Joe Codd\n*''[[Love Crazy (1941 film)|Love Crazy]]'' (1941) as Elevator Man\n*''[[Sergeant York (film)|Sergeant York]]'' (1941) as Piano Player (uncredited)\n*''[[Man at Large]]'' (1941) as Hotel Clerk\n*''[[The Maltese Falcon (1941 film)|The Maltese Falcon]]'' (1941) as Wilmer Cook\n*''[[I Wake Up Screaming]]'' (1941) as Harry Williams\n*''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'' (1941) as Harry Selby\n*''[[Ball of Fire]]'' (1941) as Waiter\n*''[[A Gentleman at Heart]]'' (1942) as Genius\n*''[[Sleepytime Gal]]'' (1942) as Ernie\n*''[[A-Haunting We Will Go (1942 film)|A-Haunting We Will Go]]'' (1942) as Frank Lucas\n*''[[Wildcat (film)|Wildcat]]'' (1942) as Harold 'Chicopee' Nevins\n*''[[Manila Calling]]'' (1942) as Gillman\n*''[[Kill or Be Killed (1942 film)|Kill or Be Killed]]'' (1942)\n*''[[Baptism of Fire]]'' (1943 documentary) as Bill\n*''[[Phantom Lady (film)|Phantom Lady]]'' (1944) as Cliff\n*''[[Up in Arms]]'' (1944) as Info Jones\n*''[[Dark Mountain (film)|Dark Mountain]]'' (1944) as Whitey\n*''[[Dark Waters (1944 film)|Dark Waters]]'' (1944) as Cleeve\n*''[[Dillinger (1945 film)|Dillinger]]'' (1945) as Kirk Otto\n*''[[Why Girls Leave Home (1945 film)|Why Girls Leave Home]]'' (1945) as Jimmy Lobo\n*''[[Blonde Alibi]]'' (1946) as Sam Collins\n*''[[Cinderella Jones]]'' (1946) as Oliver S. Patch\n*''[[The Falcon's Alibi]]'' (1946) as Nick\n*''[[Joe Palooka, Champ]]'' (1946) as Eugene\n*''[[Two Smart People]]'' (1946) as Fly Feletti\n*''[[The Big Sleep (1946 film)|The Big Sleep]]'' (1946) as Harry Jones\n*''[[Fall Guy (1947 film)|Fall Guy]]'' (1947) as Joe\n*''[[Born to Kill (1947 film)|Born to Kill]]'' (1947) as Marty\n*''[[The Long Night (1947 film)|The Long Night]]'' (1947) as Frank Dunlap\n*''[[The Gangster (1947 film)|The Gangster]]'' (1947) as Oval\n*''[[Flaxy Martin]]'' (1949) as Roper\n*''[[The Great Gatsby (1949 film)|The Great Gatsby]]'' (1949) as Klipspringer\n*''[[Behave Yourself!|Behave Yourself]]'' (1951) as Albert Jonas\n*''[[Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1952) as Eddie Forbes\n*''[[Shane (film)|Shane]]'' (1953) as Stonewall Torrey\n*''[[I, The Jury]]'' (1953) as Bobo (uncredited)\n*''[[Thunder Over the Plains]]'' (1953) as Joseph Standish\n*''[[The Outlaw's Daughter (film)|The Outlaw's Daughter]]'' (1954) as Lewis 'Tulsa' Cook\n*''[[Drum Beat]]'' (1954) as Blaine Crackel\n*''[[Timberjack (film)|Timberjack]]'' (1955) as Punky\n*''[[Trial (1955 film)|Trial]]'' (1955) as Finn\n*''[[The Indian Fighter]]'' (1955) as Briggs\n*''Indian Agent'' (1955, TV Movie) as Pete, the Cavalry Scout (uncredited)\n*''[[The Killing (film)|The Killing]]'' (1956) as George Peatty\n*''[[Accused of Murder]]'' (1956) as \"Whitey\" Pollock\n*''[[Voodoo Island]]'' (1957) as Martin Schuyler\n*''[[The Lonely Man]]'' (1957) as Willie \n*''[[Chicago Confidential]]'' (1957) as Candymouth Duggan\n*''[[Plunder Road]]'' (1957) as Skeets Jonas\n*''[[Baby Face Nelson (film)|Baby Face Nelson]]'' (1957) as Homer van Meter\n*''[[House on Haunted Hill]]'' (1959) as Watson Pritchard \n*''[[Day of the Outlaw]]'' (1959) as Larry Teter (town barber)\n*''[[Platinum High School]]'' (1960) as Harry Nesbit\n*''[[College Confidential (film)|College Confidential]]'' (1960) as Ted Blake\n*''[[One-Eyed Jacks]]'' (1961) as Carvey \n*''[[Papa's Delicate Condition]]'' (1963) as Mr. Keith\n*''[[Black Zoo]]'' (1963) as Joe\n*''[[The Haunted Palace]]'' (1963) as Peter Smith / Micah Smith \n*''[[Johnny Cool]]'' (1963) as Undertaker\n*''The Judge'' (1963, TV Movie) \n*''The Glass Cage'' (1964) as Girl's father\n*''[[Blood on the Arrow]]'' (1964) as Tex\n*''McNab's Lab'' (1966, TV