{"title_page": "Jay Ruderman", "text_new": "{{NPOV language|date=March 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jay Ruderman\n| image              = Jay Ruderman April 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Jay Ruderman (April 2014)\n| birth_name         = Jay Seth Ruderman\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Activist and philanthropist\n| children           = \n| parents            = Morton Edward Ruderman, Marcia Jortner Ruderman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Shira Menashe Ruderman|2002}}\n}}\n'''Jay Seth Ruderman''' (born March 16, 1966) is an American activist and philanthropist. He is the president of the [[Ruderman Family Foundation]].\n \n==Early life and education==\nRuderman was born on March 16, 1966. He is the oldest of three siblings, the son of Marcia and Morton E. Ruderman.<ref>{{cite web | last=Negri | first=Gloria | title=Morton Ruderman, 75; devoted life to helping others | website=BostonGlobe.com | date=2011-10-31 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/obituaries/2011/10/31/morton-ruderman-devoted-life-helping-others/rL8YpiDtdYBG1iWAWLgpwI/story.html | access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> Ruderman attended public schools in [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts]], and received his undergraduate degree in 1988 from [[Brandeis University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandeis.edu/commencement/2018/honorees/ruderman-jay.html|title=Jay Ruderman \u201988 - Commencement - Brandeis University|author=|date=|website=www.brandeis.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> where he served as president of the student body in 1986\u201387. He earned his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/tag/class-of-1993/|title=Class of 1993 - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> He began his career as Assistant District Attorney in Salem, MA and also worked as Deputy Director of AIPAC  before enlisting in the Israeli Defense Forces. He then went back to AIPAC as Leadership Director in Israel before taking his job at the Ruderman Family Foundation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncfp.org/people/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman \u2013 NCFP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Commentary on popular culture==\nRuderman publicly criticized the movie ''[[Don't Worry, He Won't Get Far on Foot]]'' for casting [[Joaquin Phoenix]] in the role of a disabled man, instead of casting an actor with a disability.<ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/joaquin-phoenix-casting-dont-worry-he-wont-get-far-on-foot-ruderman-disability-foundation-1201918359/ \"Joaquin Phoenix\u2019s \u2018Don\u2019t Worry, He Won\u2019t Get Far on Foot\u2019 Casting Slammed as Offensive by Ruderman Disability Foundation\"] ''IndieWire''. Retrieved 2018-03-22.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Ruderman similarly condemned<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/alec-baldwin-criticized-for-portraying-blind-man-in-new-film-w491281|title=Alec Baldwin Criticized for Portraying Blind Man in Upcoming Film|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> the movie ''[[Blind (2016 film)|Blind]]'' starring [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Demi Moore]] on grounds that Baldwin played a blind character. Ruderman's main claim is that the movie \"is just the latest example of treating disability as a costume.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/blind-alec-baldwin-controversy-1202488128/|title=Disability Organization Slams \u2018Blind\u2019 for Casting Alec Baldwin in Lead Role|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=July 6, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-july-disability-organization-condemns-1499273816-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Blue Ivy makes her rap debut on Jay-Z's new album; Angela Lansbury, Emily Watson to star in 'Little Women'|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He likened the casting of able-bodied actors to portray characters with disabilities to blackface<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/06/how-alec-baldwin-casting-in-blind-is-part-of-a-catch-22-for-disabled-actors|title=How Alec Baldwin's casting in Blind is part of a catch-22 for disabled actors|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2017-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and states that it's time for society to condemn the practice just like casting white actors to play black characters is no longer socially acceptable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/07/alec-baldwin-new-movie-blind-disability-rights-ableism-1201851800/|title=Alec Baldwin\u2019s New Movie \u2018Blind\u2019 Criticized By Disability Rights Group {{!}} IndieWire|last=Dry|first=Jude|website=www.indiewire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> The incident led to written exchanges between the movie's director, [[Michael Mailer]], and Ruderman, both published by the industry publication Deadline.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-alec-baldwin-backlash-director-responds-michael-mailer-1202129011/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Director Addresses Backlash Over Casting Alec Baldwin And Not Disabled Actor In Lead Role|last=Mailer|first=Michael|date=2017-07-14|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-movie-controversy-alec-baldwin-ruderman-foundation-responds-guest-column-1202130794/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Movie: Ruderman Foundation Responds To Director Over Alec Baldwin Casting Flap|last=Ruderman|first=Jay|date=2017-07-18|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of the 2016 film ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]'', Ruderman condemned the film's widely criticized portrayal of disability, in which the protagonist{{ndash}}who is paralyzed{{ndash}}ends up committing suicide because he feels his life is not worth living. Ruderman was widely quoted as stating, \"To the millions of people with significant disabilities currently leading fulfilling, rich lives, it posits that they are better off committing suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/06/05/me-before-you-ending-director-responds|title='Me Before You' director responds to controversy over film's ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/celebrity/celebrity-gossip/2016/6/me-before-you-movie-ending/|title=The director of Me Before You is #sorrynotsorry about its controversial ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Ruderman's second major point in this controversy was that it is problematic for an able-bodied actor to play a character with a disability, a topic he often speaks up about.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-woodburn-ruderman-disability-stats-tv-20160711-snap-story.html|title=Why are we OK with disability drag in Hollywood?|date=2016-07-11|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-03-10|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nIn addition to commenting on movie productions, Ruderman recently has released two white papers focusing on television content and people with disabilities, as well as a white paper on first responders and suicide. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magicvalley.com/opinion/columnists/other-view-suicide-prevention-to-priority-for-first-responders/article_fad4582a-e631-55b0-86a7-7084b1f6b673.html|title=Other View: Suicide Prevention to Priority for First Responders|last=HERALD|first=FROM THE PANAMA CITY NEWS|website=Twin Falls Times-News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> In 2019 Jay Ruderman enacted a scholarship for students with disabilities at Yale School of Drama with the goal of increasing  authentic representation for disabilities in Hollywood.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/disabled-actors-say-theyre-the-last-civil-rights-movement-in-hollywood-hardly-anyones-discussing-it/2019/01/24/cbde57a2-1817-11e9-9ebf-c5fed1b7a081_story.html</ref> Since then, Ruderman has also focused on increasing authentic representation in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/ruderman-foundation-responds-stronger-david-gordon-green|title=Authentic auditioning makes movies stronger, so give disabled actors a chance: advocacy group|publisher=Metro}}</ref> Despite recent improvements in authentic casting in 2020, Ruderman has emphasized that the low representation on screen had implications in shaping attitudes towards people with disabilities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/arts/television/disabled-hollywood.html|title=For the Disabled in Hollywood, Report Finds Hints of Progress|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nRuderman works closely with actors, disability activists and celebrities in spreading awareness of disability inclusion in the entertainment industry. Some of them serve on the Ruderman Family Foundation\u2019s International Advisory Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rudermanfoundation.org/about-us/international-advisory-council/|title=International Advisory Council|website=Ruderman Family Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> Jay Ruderman also partnered with Variety Magazine for Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit, where panelist discussed disability inclusion in entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/viola-davis-julius-tennon-marlee-matlin-variety-2019-inclusion-summit-1203206549/|title=Viola Davis, Julius Tennon, Marlee Matlin to Keynote Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit|last=Moreau|first=Jordan|last2=Moreau|first2=Jordan|date=2019-05-07|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/new-study-networks-10-billion-disabled-actors-1203354776/|title=New Study Shows Networks Leave $10 Billion on the Table by Not Casting Disabled Actors|last=Bell|first=BreAnna|last2=Bell|first2=BreAnna|date=2019-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Ruderman and his wife have also been given credit for helping to bring disability inclusion to the Oscars in 2020, as Zack Gottsagen, an actor who has Down syndrome, presented an award with actor Shia LaBeouf. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/02/how-the-rudermans-helped-bring-disability-awareness-to-the-oscars/|title=How the Rudermans helped bring disability awareness to the Oscars|last=February 10|first=Debra Nussbaum Cohen|last2=2020|date=2020-02-10|website=Jewish Insider|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2020 Sundance Film Festival, he helped to bring about more accessibility as well as inclusion of people with disabilities and diversity throughout the Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-film-festival-partnership-extends-accessibility-attendees-disabilities-1270602|title=Sundance Partnership Extends Accessibility for Attendees With Disabilities|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In March of 2020, Ruderman helped bring together many in the entertainment industry to honor Peter and Bobby Farrelly with the Morton E. Ruderman Award in Inclusion for their inclusion of actors with disabilities in their movies. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/farrelly-brothers-inclusion-activism-1203524533/|title=Farrelly Brothers Saluted for Inclusion and Activism|last=Gray|first=Tim|last2=Gray|first2=Tim|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn February of 2019, a group of young activists called LINK20, with the help of Ruderman, was successful in getting Major League Baseball to change its 'disabled list' to the 'injured list.' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-group-convinced-mlb-to-change-disabled-list-to-injured-list/|title=Jewish group convinced MLB to change \u2018disabled list\u2019 to \u2018injured list\u2019|last=Oster|first=Marcy|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May of 2019, Jay Ruderman announced the Foundation\u2019s Seal of Authentic Representation. The Seal is awarded to television or feature film projects featuring actors with disabilities in substantial speaking roles, and is the premier recognition for those in the entertainment creative community who show the commitment toward full inclusiveness in popular culture.  \n\nIn November of 2015, Ruderman called out then-candidate Trump for mimicking the disability of [[The New York Times|New York Times]] writer Serge Kovaleski, who suffered from a congenital condition that affects joint movement. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/ruderman-foundation-president-offers-trump-sensitivity-training/|title=Ruderman Foundation President Offers Trump Sensitivity Training|date=2015-11-30|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>  \n\nRuderman also contributes a blog on a variety of topics for ''The Times of Israel.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman's Blog|website=blogs.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> He is serving on the board of directors for the National Organization on Disability <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nod.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=National Organization on Disability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> and on the board of governors for the University of Haifa. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-us/members-of-the-board-of-governors/22-hebrew/45-heb/45-prof-robert-uri-alter-usa-comparative-literature-researcher-6|title=Mrs. Shira and Mr. Jay Ruderman (Israel/USA), Philanthropists|last=User|first=Super|website=bogcms.haifa.ac.il|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== US - Israel Relations ==\nRuderman is also active in US-Israel relations, seeking to foster a better understanding of American Jewry among Israeli opinion leaders. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/joe-lieberman-us-israel-relations-to-become-very-productive/|title=Joe Lieberman: US-Israel relations about to become \u2018very productive\u2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nHe was among several signatories of an ad expressing disappointment with the Israeli government about its decision to renege on a plan for egalitarian prayer at the Western Wall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/major-us-jewish-philanthropists-decry-western-wall-backtrack-conversion-bill/|title=Major US Jewish philanthropists decry Western Wall backtrack, conversion bill|last=staff|first=T. O. I.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> Ruderman also condemned the Israel\u2019s Minister of Education\u2019s comments on intermarriage of US Jews. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/education-minister-calls-intermarriage-in-us-a-second-holocaust/|title=Israel\u2019s education minister: Intermarriage among US Jews \u2018like second Holocaust\u2019|last=JTA and TOI staff|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nRuderman was quoted as saying the \"doomsday talks of an irreversible chasm between Israel and the American Jewish community were mistaken,\" in light of a recent [[Ruderman Family Foundation]] survey and in response to the notion that the bond between U.S. Jews and Israel is weakening. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/love-for-israel-survives-a-decade-of-discord/|title=Love for Israel Survives a Decade of Discord|last=Editors|first=Jewish Week|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== COVID-19 ==\nIn response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Ruderman conveyed concerns about the effects the pandemic would have on the mental health of first responders and healthcare workers. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/12/nation/coronavirus-fight-progresses-focus-first-responders-mental-health/|title=As coronavirus fight progresses, a focus on first responders\u2019 mental health - The Boston Globe|last=Staff|first=Gal Tziperman Lotan Globe|last2=April 12|first2=Updated|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=2020|last4=Comments|first4=8:44 p m Email to a Friend Share on Facebook Share on TwitterPrint this Article View}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2016 Ruderman was named by ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' as one of the 50 most influential Jews of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46 - Jay and Shira Ruderman - TRENDING STORIES - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n* Honorary doctorate from [[University of Haifa]], Israel (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/Ruderman-Heb.pdf|title=Jay, Shira Ruderman|last=|first=|date=June 2, 2015|website=University of Haifa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate from [[Brandeis University]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/2018/05/17/jay-ruderman-93-to-receive-an-honorary-degree-from-brandeis-university/|title=Jay Ruderman (\u201993) to Receive an Honorary Degree from Brandeis University - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Jacob Rader Marcus Award from the [[American Jewish Archives]] (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/09/19/jay-and-shira-ruderman-receive-jacob-rader-marcus-award/|title=Jay and Shira Ruderman receive Jacob Rader Marcus Award|last=says|first=Suzanne Green|date=2019-09-19|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Media Access Awards [[SAG-AFTRA]] Disability Awareness Award (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/media-access-awards-honor-good-doctor-peanut-butter-falcon-nyle-dimarco-1251834|title=Media Access Awards to Honor 'The Good Doctor,' 'The Peanut Butter Falcon' and Nyle DiMarco (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Essays and Publications ==\n\n* Jay [https://www.jpost.com/author/jay-ruderman Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]]\n* Jay [https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Times of Israel|Times of Israel]]\n* Jay [http://fathomjournal.org/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on [[Fathom Journal]]\n*\"Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn't Continue to Call the Shots at Jewish Charities\" on [[The Chronicle of Philanthropy|Chronicle of Philanthropy]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropy.com/article/Ultrawealthy-Donors/246421/|title=Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn\u2019t Continue to Call All the Shots at Jewish Charities (Opinion)|date=2019-06-03|website=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community\" on eJewish Philanthropy <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ejewishphilanthropy.com/leveraging-israeli-americans-for-the-benefit-of-the-wider-community/|title=Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community|date=2019-12-02|website=eJewish Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Stop Enabling Donors Outsized Influence on Jewish Life\" on [[The Forward]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/opinion/322972/stop-enabling-donors-outsized-influence-on-jewish-life/|title=Stop Enabling Donors' Outsized Influence on Jewish Life|last=RudermanOct 22|first=Jay|last2=Ulinich|first2=2015Anya|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"People with Disabilities are the Forgotten Vulnerable\" on [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/healthcare/491616-people-with-disabilities-are-the-forgotten-vulnerable|title=People with disabilities are the forgotten vulnerable community in the age of COVID-19|last=Jordan|first=Chuck|date=2020-04-07|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRuderman is married to Israeli-American Shira Menashe Ruderman. They live in the Greater Boston area and have four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Linde|first1=Steve|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46|url=http://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|access-date=March 12, 2018|publisher=The Jerusalem Post|date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruderman, Jay}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Massachusetts\u200e]]\n[[Category:Disability rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{NPOV language|date=March 2020}}\n{{Peacock|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jay Ruderman\n| image              = Jay Ruderman April 2014.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Jay Ruderman (April 2014)\n| birth_name         = Jay Seth Ruderman\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1966|3|16}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Activist and philanthropist\n| children           = \n| parents            = Morton Edward Ruderman, Marcia Jortner Ruderman\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Shira Menashe Ruderman|2002}}\n}}\n'''Jay Seth Ruderman''' (born March 16, 1966) is an American activist and philanthropist. He is the president of the [[Ruderman Family Foundation]].\n \n==Early life and education==\nRuderman was born on March 16, 1966. He is the oldest of three siblings, the son of Marcia and Morton E. Ruderman.<ref>{{cite web | last=Negri | first=Gloria | title=Morton Ruderman, 75; devoted life to helping others | website=BostonGlobe.com | date=2011-10-31 | url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/obituaries/2011/10/31/morton-ruderman-devoted-life-helping-others/rL8YpiDtdYBG1iWAWLgpwI/story.html | access-date=2018-02-22}}</ref> Ruderman attended public schools in [[Lynnfield, Massachusetts]], and received his undergraduate degree in 1988 from [[Brandeis University]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.brandeis.edu/commencement/2018/honorees/ruderman-jay.html|title=Jay Ruderman \u201988 - Commencement - Brandeis University|author=|date=|website=www.brandeis.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> where he served as president of the student body in 1986\u201387. He earned his [[Juris Doctor|JD]] from [[Boston University School of Law]] in 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/tag/class-of-1993/|title=Class of 1993 - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> He began his career as Assistant District Attorney in Salem, MA and also worked as Deputy Director of AIPAC  before enlisting in the Israeli Defense Forces. He then went back to AIPAC as Leadership Director in Israel before taking his job at the Ruderman Family Foundation. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncfp.org/people/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman \u2013 NCFP|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Commentary on popular culture==\nRuderman publicly criticized the movie ''[[Don't Worry, He Won't Get Far on Foot]]'' for casting [[Joaquin Phoenix]] in the role of a disabled man, instead of casting an actor with a disability.<ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/joaquin-phoenix-casting-dont-worry-he-wont-get-far-on-foot-ruderman-disability-foundation-1201918359/ \"Joaquin Phoenix\u2019s \u2018Don\u2019t Worry, He Won\u2019t Get Far on Foot\u2019 Casting Slammed as Offensive by Ruderman Disability Foundation\"] ''IndieWire''. Retrieved 2018-03-22.</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Ruderman similarly condemned<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/alec-baldwin-criticized-for-portraying-blind-man-in-new-film-w491281|title=Alec Baldwin Criticized for Portraying Blind Man in Upcoming Film|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> the movie ''[[Blind (2016 film)|Blind]]'' starring [[Alec Baldwin]] and [[Demi Moore]] on grounds that Baldwin played a blind character. Ruderman's main claim is that the movie \"is just the latest example of treating disability as a costume.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/blind-alec-baldwin-controversy-1202488128/|title=Disability Organization Slams \u2018Blind\u2019 for Casting Alec Baldwin in Lead Role|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|date=July 6, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=July 7, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-et-entertainment-news-updates-july-disability-organization-condemns-1499273816-htmlstory.html|title=Today in Entertainment: Blue Ivy makes her rap debut on Jay-Z's new album; Angela Lansbury, Emily Watson to star in 'Little Women'|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> He likened the casting of able-bodied actors to portray characters with disabilities to blackface<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2017/jul/06/how-alec-baldwin-casting-in-blind-is-part-of-a-catch-22-for-disabled-actors|title=How Alec Baldwin's casting in Blind is part of a catch-22 for disabled actors|last=Ellis-Petersen|first=Hannah|date=2017-07-06|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-07-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and states that it's time for society to condemn the practice just like casting white actors to play black characters is no longer socially acceptable.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2017/07/alec-baldwin-new-movie-blind-disability-rights-ableism-1201851800/|title=Alec Baldwin\u2019s New Movie \u2018Blind\u2019 Criticized By Disability Rights Group {{!}} IndieWire|last=Dry|first=Jude|website=www.indiewire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-07-07}}</ref> The incident led to written exchanges between the movie's director, [[Michael Mailer]], and Ruderman, both published by the industry publication Deadline.com.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-alec-baldwin-backlash-director-responds-michael-mailer-1202129011/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Director Addresses Backlash Over Casting Alec Baldwin And Not Disabled Actor In Lead Role|last=Mailer|first=Michael|date=2017-07-14|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2017/07/blind-movie-controversy-alec-baldwin-ruderman-foundation-responds-guest-column-1202130794/|title=\u2018Blind\u2019 Movie: Ruderman Foundation Responds To Director Over Alec Baldwin Casting Flap|last=Ruderman|first=Jay|date=2017-07-18|work=Deadline|access-date=2017-07-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the release of the 2016 film ''[[Me Before You (film)|Me Before You]]'', Ruderman condemned the film's widely criticized portrayal of disability, in which the protagonist{{ndash}}who is paralyzed{{ndash}}ends up committing suicide because he feels his life is not worth living. Ruderman was widely quoted as stating, \"To the millions of people with significant disabilities currently leading fulfilling, rich lives, it posits that they are better off committing suicide.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/06/05/me-before-you-ending-director-responds|title='Me Before You' director responds to controversy over film's ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cosmopolitan.com.au/celebrity/celebrity-gossip/2016/6/me-before-you-movie-ending/|title=The director of Me Before You is #sorrynotsorry about its controversial ending|access-date=2016-07-01}}</ref> Ruderman's second major point in this controversy was that it is problematic for an able-bodied actor to play a character with a disability, a topic he often speaks up about.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-woodburn-ruderman-disability-stats-tv-20160711-snap-story.html|title=Why are we OK with disability drag in Hollywood?|date=2016-07-11|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2017-03-10|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\n== Activism ==\nIn addition to commenting on movie productions, Ruderman recently has released two white papers focusing on television content and people with disabilities, as well as a white paper on first responders and suicide. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://magicvalley.com/opinion/columnists/other-view-suicide-prevention-to-priority-for-first-responders/article_fad4582a-e631-55b0-86a7-7084b1f6b673.html|title=Other View: Suicide Prevention to Priority for First Responders|last=HERALD|first=FROM THE PANAMA CITY NEWS|website=Twin Falls Times-News|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref> In 2019 Jay Ruderman enacted a scholarship for students with disabilities at Yale School of Drama with the goal of increasing  authentic representation for disabilities in Hollywood.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/disabled-actors-say-theyre-the-last-civil-rights-movement-in-hollywood-hardly-anyones-discussing-it/2019/01/24/cbde57a2-1817-11e9-9ebf-c5fed1b7a081_story.html</ref> Since then, Ruderman has also focused on increasing authentic representation in the entertainment industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metro.us/entertainment/movies/ruderman-foundation-responds-stronger-david-gordon-green|title=Authentic auditioning makes movies stronger, so give disabled actors a chance: advocacy group|publisher=Metro}}</ref> Despite recent improvements in authentic casting in 2020, Ruderman has emphasized that the low representation on screen had implications in shaping attitudes towards people with disabilities. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/arts/television/disabled-hollywood.html|title=For the Disabled in Hollywood, Report Finds Hints of Progress|last=Buckley|first=Cara|date=2020-02-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-06|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nRuderman works closely with actors, disability activists and celebrities in spreading awareness of disability inclusion in the entertainment industry. Some of them serve on the Ruderman Family Foundation\u2019s International Advisory Council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rudermanfoundation.org/about-us/international-advisory-council/|title=International Advisory Council|website=Ruderman Family Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-08}}</ref> Jay Ruderman also partnered with Variety Magazine for Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit, where panelist discussed disability inclusion in entertainment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/viola-davis-julius-tennon-marlee-matlin-variety-2019-inclusion-summit-1203206549/|title=Viola Davis, Julius Tennon, Marlee Matlin to Keynote Variety\u2019s 2019 Inclusion Summit|last=Moreau|first=Jordan|last2=Moreau|first2=Jordan|date=2019-05-07|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/new-study-networks-10-billion-disabled-actors-1203354776/|title=New Study Shows Networks Leave $10 Billion on the Table by Not Casting Disabled Actors|last=Bell|first=BreAnna|last2=Bell|first2=BreAnna|date=2019-10-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-11-05}}</ref> Ruderman and his wife have also been given credit for helping to bring disability inclusion to the Oscars in 2020, as Zack Gottsagen, an actor who has Down syndrome, presented an award with actor Shia LaBeouf. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishinsider.com/2020/02/how-the-rudermans-helped-bring-disability-awareness-to-the-oscars/|title=How the Rudermans helped bring disability awareness to the Oscars|last=February 10|first=Debra Nussbaum Cohen|last2=2020|date=2020-02-10|website=Jewish Insider|access-date=2020-02-12}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2020 Sundance Film Festival, he helped to bring about more accessibility as well as inclusion of people with disabilities and diversity throughout the Festival. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sundance-film-festival-partnership-extends-accessibility-attendees-disabilities-1270602|title=Sundance Partnership Extends Accessibility for Attendees With Disabilities|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref> In March of 2020, Ruderman helped bring together many in the entertainment industry to honor Peter and Bobby Farrelly with the Morton E. Ruderman Award in Inclusion for their inclusion of actors with disabilities in their movies. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/farrelly-brothers-inclusion-activism-1203524533/|title=Farrelly Brothers Saluted for Inclusion and Activism|last=Gray|first=Tim|last2=Gray|first2=Tim|date=2020-03-05|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn February of 2019, a group of young activists called LINK20, with the help of Ruderman, was successful in getting Major League Baseball to change its 'disabled list' to the 'injured list.' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/jewish-group-convinced-mlb-to-change-disabled-list-to-injured-list/|title=Jewish group convinced MLB to change \u2018disabled list\u2019 to \u2018injured list\u2019|last=Oster|first=Marcy|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n\nIn May of 2019, Jay Ruderman announced the Foundation\u2019s Seal of Authentic Representation. The Seal is awarded to television or feature film projects featuring actors with disabilities in substantial speaking roles, and is the premier recognition for those in the entertainment creative community who show the commitment toward full inclusiveness in popular culture.  \n\nIn November of 2015, Ruderman called out then-candidate Trump for mimicking the disability of [[The New York Times|New York Times]] writer Serge Kovaleski, who suffered from a congenital condition that affects joint movement. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/ruderman-foundation-president-offers-trump-sensitivity-training/|title=Ruderman Foundation President Offers Trump Sensitivity Training|date=2015-11-30|website=Non Profit News {{!}} Nonprofit Quarterly|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>  \n\nRuderman also contributes a blog on a variety of topics for ''The Times of Israel.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/jay-ruderman/|title=Jay Ruderman's Blog|website=blogs.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> He is serving on the board of directors for the National Organization on Disability <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nod.org/about/our-board/|title=Our Board|website=National Organization on Disability|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> and on the board of governors for the University of Haifa. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/index.php/en/about-us/members-of-the-board-of-governors/22-hebrew/45-heb/45-prof-robert-uri-alter-usa-comparative-literature-researcher-6|title=Mrs. Shira and Mr. Jay Ruderman (Israel/USA), Philanthropists|last=User|first=Super|website=bogcms.haifa.ac.il|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n\n== US - Israel Relations ==\nRuderman is also active in US-Israel relations, seeking to foster a better understanding of American Jewry among Israeli opinion leaders. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/joe-lieberman-us-israel-relations-to-become-very-productive/|title=Joe Lieberman: US-Israel relations about to become \u2018very productive\u2019|last=Ahren|first=Raphael|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nHe was among several signatories of an ad expressing disappointment with the Israeli government about its decision to renege on a plan for egalitarian prayer at the Western Wall. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/major-us-jewish-philanthropists-decry-western-wall-backtrack-conversion-bill/|title=Major US Jewish philanthropists decry Western Wall backtrack, conversion bill|last=staff|first=T. O. I.|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> Ruderman also condemned the Israel\u2019s Minister of Education\u2019s comments on intermarriage of US Jews. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/education-minister-calls-intermarriage-in-us-a-second-holocaust/|title=Israel\u2019s education minister: Intermarriage among US Jews \u2018like second Holocaust\u2019|last=JTA and TOI staff|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref> \n\nRuderman was quoted as saying the \"doomsday talks of an irreversible chasm between Israel and the American Jewish community were mistaken,\" in light of a recent [[Ruderman Family Foundation]] survey and in response to the notion that the bond between U.S. Jews and Israel is weakening. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/love-for-israel-survives-a-decade-of-discord/|title=Love for Israel Survives a Decade of Discord|last=Editors|first=Jewish Week|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n<br />\n\n== COVID-19 ==\nIn response to the COVID-19 pandemic, Ruderman conveyed concerns about the effects the pandemic would have have on the mental health of first responders and healthcare workers. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/04/12/nation/coronavirus-fight-progresses-focus-first-responders-mental-health/|title=As coronavirus fight progresses, a focus on first responders\u2019 mental health - The Boston Globe|last=Staff|first=Gal Tziperman Lotan Globe|last2=April 12|first2=Updated|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14|last3=2020|last4=Comments|first4=8:44 p m Email to a Friend Share on Facebook Share on TwitterPrint this Article View}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nIn 2016 Ruderman was named by ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]'' as one of the 50 most influential Jews of the year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46 - Jay and Shira Ruderman - TRENDING STORIES - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n\n* Honorary doctorate from [[University of Haifa]], Israel (2015)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bogcms.haifa.ac.il/images/Ruderman-Heb.pdf|title=Jay, Shira Ruderman|last=|first=|date=June 2, 2015|website=University of Haifa|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* Honorary doctorate from [[Brandeis University]] (2018)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/2018/05/17/jay-ruderman-93-to-receive-an-honorary-degree-from-brandeis-university/|title=Jay Ruderman (\u201993) to Receive an Honorary Degree from Brandeis University - School of Law|author=|date=|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* Jacob Rader Marcus Award from the [[American Jewish Archives]] (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.org/2019/09/19/jay-and-shira-ruderman-receive-jacob-rader-marcus-award/|title=Jay and Shira Ruderman receive Jacob Rader Marcus Award|last=says|first=Suzanne Green|date=2019-09-19|website=Jewish Journal|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n* Media Access Awards [[SAG-AFTRA]] Disability Awareness Award (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/media-access-awards-honor-good-doctor-peanut-butter-falcon-nyle-dimarco-1251834|title=Media Access Awards to Honor 'The Good Doctor,' 'The Peanut Butter Falcon' and Nyle DiMarco (Exclusive)|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-19}}</ref>\n\n== Essays and Publications ==\n\n* Jay [https://www.jpost.com/author/jay-ruderman Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Jerusalem Post|Jerusalem Post]]\n* Jay [https://blogs.timesofisrael.com/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on the [[The Times of Israel|Times of Israel]]\n* Jay [http://fathomjournal.org/author/jay-ruderman/ Ruderman's Author Page] on [[Fathom Journal]]\n*\"Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn't Continue to Call the Shots at Jewish Charities\" on [[The Chronicle of Philanthropy|Chronicle of Philanthropy]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philanthropy.com/article/Ultrawealthy-Donors/246421/|title=Ultrawealthy Donors Shouldn\u2019t Continue to Call All the Shots at Jewish Charities (Opinion)|date=2019-06-03|website=The Chronicle of Philanthropy|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community\" on eJewish Philanthropy <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ejewishphilanthropy.com/leveraging-israeli-americans-for-the-benefit-of-the-wider-community/|title=Leveraging Israeli-Americans for the Benefit of the Wider Community|date=2019-12-02|website=eJewish Philanthropy|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"Stop Enabling Donors Outsized Influence on Jewish Life\" on [[The Forward]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://forward.com/opinion/322972/stop-enabling-donors-outsized-influence-on-jewish-life/|title=Stop Enabling Donors' Outsized Influence on Jewish Life|last=RudermanOct 22|first=Jay|last2=Ulinich|first2=2015Anya|website=The Forward|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n*\"People with Disabilities are the Forgotten Vulnerable\" on [[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/healthcare/491616-people-with-disabilities-are-the-forgotten-vulnerable|title=People with disabilities are the forgotten vulnerable community in the age of COVID-19|last=Jordan|first=Chuck|date=2020-04-07|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRuderman is married to Israeli-American Shira Menashe Ruderman. They live in the Greater Boston area and have four children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Linde|first1=Steve|title=Jerusalem Post 50 Most Influential Jews: Number 46|url=http://www.jpost.com/Not-Just-News/Jerusalem-Post-50-Most-Influential-Jews-Number-46-Jay-and-Shira-Ruderman-469086|access-date=March 12, 2018|publisher=The Jerusalem Post|date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ruderman, Jay}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Philanthropists from Massachusetts\u200e]]\n[[Category:Disability rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Ruderman"}
{"title_page": "August Busch IV", "text_new": "{{About|the 5th generation brewing magnate|other persons|Busch (surname)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = August Busch IV\n| image       = August A. Busch IV with Budweiser Clydesdale.jpg\n| caption     = Busch with a Budweiser Clydesdale in 2006\n| birth_name  = August Adolphus Busch IV\n| occupation  = Board member of [[Anheuser-Busch InBev]]<br/>Retired president and CEO, [[Anheuser-Busch|Anheuser-Busch Companies, Inc.]]<br/>Retired director, [[FedEx]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1964|6|15}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]], U.S.\n| alma_mater  = [[Saint Louis University]]<br/>[[VLB Berlin]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| spouse      = Kathryn \"Kate\" Thatcher <small>(2006-2009) divorced</small>\n| parents     = [[August Busch III]] and Susan (Hornibrook) Busch\n}}\n\n'''August Adolphus Busch IV''' (born June 15, 1964) is an American businessman and former CEO of [[Anheuser-Busch]]. He was the last of the family to control the company, which was purchased in a hostile takeover in 2008 by [[InBev]]. Busch IV was known for his marketing leadership, where his history as head of the Anheuser-Busch marketing department garnered ten straight ''USA Today'' [[Super Bowl Ad Meter]] awards, as well as awards at [[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]] and the [[Clio Awards|Grand Clio]].<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_27th_busch_honors|title=BUSCH FAMILY TO BE HONORED FOR DECADES OF OUTSTANDING CONTRIBUTIONS TO SPORTS TELEVISION BY NATIONAL TELEVISION ACADEMY {{!}} The Emmy Awards - The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://admeter.usatoday.com/|title=Ad Meter|website=Ad Meter|language=en|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/close-up-newsmaker-august-busch-iv---man-yes-budweisers-whassup-august-busch-scoops-highest-advertisers-award-cannes/46935|title=CLOSE-UP: NEWSMAKER/AUGUST BUSCH IV - The man who said yes to Budweiser's 'whassup?'. August Busch scoops the highest advertiser's award at Cannes|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> He also served as a director of shipping giant [[FedEx]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FedEx |url=http://www.fedex.com/us/investorrelations/financialinfo/2005annualreport/online/board.html |website=FedEx.com}}</ref> Busch has been involved in a number of legal incidents during his lifetime.<ref name=knoedelseder/>\n\n==Early life==\nHe is a great-great-grandson of [[Anheuser-Busch]] founder [[Adolphus Busch]], and a great-great-great-grandson of [[Eberhard Anheuser]] who originally purchased the brewery in 1860. He is the son of Susan (Hornibrook) and [[August Busch III]], the former chairman, president and CEO of the company.\n\nBusch's parents divorced when he was five, and he lived with his mother.  His time with his father was mostly spent at the brewery and their relationship was, for the most part, professional.<ref name=ACFfHL>Kosmodel, David, \"Anheuser CEO Fight for His Legacy,\" ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', A1, May 27, 2008</ref>\n\n===Education===\n\nBusch received a bachelor's degree in finance and later a master's degree in business administration from [[Saint Louis University]]. He later served on the university's board of trustees.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Oliver |first1=Garrett |title=The Oxford Companion to Beer |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=197 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ga4MYyZq-RMC&pg=PA197&lpg=PA197&dq=%22august+busch+iv%22+and+%22saint+Louis+university%22&source=bl&ots=qEVqXZOln3&sig=ACfU3U1PH24PEy41L0U00rv3DFoZEdCzFQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwid0sO_ldHkAhWDTt8KHUAKDiA4ChDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22august%20busch%20iv%22%20and%20%22saint%20Louis%20university%22&f=false |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his early twenties, Busch earned a brewmaster's degree from Versuchs und Lehranstalt fur Brauerei, a brewing institute in Berlin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ludington |first1=Callaway |title=Bud Man |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1991-06-14-9102220836-story.html |accessdate=14 September 2019 |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=June 14, 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Anheuser-Busch==\n\n===Early years===\nAfter graduation he followed the family tradition of starting at the bottom of [[Anheuser-Busch]]. He worked as a brewing apprentice in the Old Malt House as a union member of Brewers & Maltsters Local 6 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], as an intern in the culture yeast center, and later as a foreman in packaging and shipping operations.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 1989, he moved into marketing, working on the [[Bud Dry]] brand launch. Although the launch was considered a success, the product ultimately proved to be unsuccessful.\n\nBusch's father initially opposed the campaign; he later admitted \"I've lost the ability to understand the 21- to 30-year-olds the way I used to.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm | work=CNN | title=Bud-Weis-Heir August Busch Iv Is Rebellious, Risk-Taking--And (Nearly) Ready To Rule The World's Largest Brewer | first=Patricia | last=Sellers | date=January 13, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Busch was named vice president of brand management. In 1996, he became vice president of marketing. Busch was promoted in 2000 to group vice president of marketing and wholesale operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beerandbrewing.com/dictionary/Cd92zGLNQp|title=Busch, August IV|last=|first=|date=|website=Craft Beer and Brewing Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Under his leadership, the company emphasized more creative and often humorous advertising. In an interview with Fortune magazine, he recounted a conversation with his father August Busch III, then the company's president and CEO, that Budweiser sales would grow only if the iconic brand's identity was reinvented. \"There was a culture weaved into the Budweiser brand... No one wanted to change it,\" Busch IV told the magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm|title=Bud-Weis-Heir August Busch IV Is Rebellious, Risk-Taking--and (Nearly) Ready to Rule the World's Largest Brewer|last=Sellers|first=Patricia|date=January 13, 1997|work=Fortune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The new advertising campaigns launched by Busch IV cemented his reputation for marketing instincts. The Budweiser and Bud Light commercials won the [[USA Today Super Bowl Ad Meter]]\u00a0every year from 1999 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://admeter.usatoday.com/2019/01/23/all-time-greatest-super-bowl-commercials/|title=All 31 Super Bowl Ad Meter-winning commercials from 1989 to 2018|last=Siegel|first=Alan|date=January 23, 2019|website=USA Today's Ad Meter website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Budweiser frogs, penguins, ants, lizards ===\nBusch IV focused the marketing department on humor, youth, animals, and tradition. He insisted to his father that his department could make splashy\u2014yet risky\u2014ads targeted at a younger demographic. That led to the creation of the [[Budweiser Frogs]] advertising campaign featuring puppet frogs chirping \"Bud\", \"Weis\", and \"Er\". Other campaigns overseen by Busch IV featured a friendly alligator, a sinister penguin with the catchphrase \"doobie doobie do\", partying ants, and a self-absorbed lizard named Louie. The ads, according to Fortune Magazine, helped Anheuser-Busch stock rise by 27% in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm|title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR AUGUST BUSCH IV IS REBELLIOUS, RISK-TAKING--AND (NEARLY) READY TO RULE THE WORLD'S LARGEST BREWER. - January 13, 1997|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> \u00a0By 1998, the company achieved its best sales year ever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/21/business/media-business-advertising-anheuser-busch-after-its-best-sales-year-ever.html|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING; Anheuser-Busch, after its best sales year ever, is spending a record sum on this year's Super Bowl.|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=1999-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman and InBev takeover===\n[[File:AugustWarren.png|thumb|Former Anheuser-Busch CEO August Busch IV (right) with Berkshire Hathaway Chairman Warren Buffett (left). 2006]]\nIn 2002, Busch (and other family members) were passed over when the company named [[Patrick Stokes (businessman)|Patrick Stokes]] as its first non-family president and CEO.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/patrick-t-stokes/4237 |title=Patrick T. Stokes Profile - Forbes.com |publisher=People.forbes.com |date= |accessdate=December 26, 2010}}</ref>  Busch's father had said that he owns 1% of the stock and that the \"board of directors calls the shots\" at the company.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm |title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR AUGUST BUSCH IV IS REBELLIOUS, RISK-TAKING-AND (NEARLY) READY TO RULE THE WORLD'S LARGEST BREWER.|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=December 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, as president of the company, Busch IV announced the brewer had purchased the 20-year naming rights to a new [[Busch Stadium]], the home of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. Team owner William Dewitt Jr. said: \u201cFrom the day we began planning for the new ballpark, we wanted to keep the name \u2018Busch Stadium.' August Busch IV and Anheuser-Busch share our vision for continuing that tradition for our great fans and the entire St. Louis community.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805220653/http://www.anheuser-busch.com/news/BuschStadium_080404.htm|title=The Tradition Continues: St. Louis Cardinals to Play in Third 'Busch Stadium'|last=|first=|date=2004-08-05|website=www.anheuser-busch.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> Dewitt, as part of an ownership group, had purchased the team from the brewery in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/23/sports/busch-to-sell-cardinals.html|title=Busch to Sell Cardinals|last=|first=|date=1995-12-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBusch became president and CEO effective December 2006. Busch's father had been criticized for not expanding globally and leaving the company open for acquisition.  In 2007, August and the directors began discussions to acquire [[Diageo]] but the deal never advanced.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Kesmodel |first=David |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2010/09/29/new-book-says-busch-family-lost-budweiser-amid-infighting-missed-deals/ |title=New Book Says Busch Family Lost Budweiser Amid Infighting, Missed Deals - Deal Journal - WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=September 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLess than 18 months into Busch's tenure, rumors circulated that [[InBev]] was attempting to buy the company.  In April 2008, Busch told beer distributors that Anheuser-Busch would never be bought \"on my watch.\"  A-B stock had closed at $49.20 on April 30, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=63607&p=irol-stocklookup |title=Anheuser-Busch Companies - Historical Price Lookup |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date=March 26, 1996 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref>  InBev offered $65 per share in June, and Busch refused.  Prior to InBev's offer, A-B's stock had never been higher than $51.97.  In hopes of keeping its independence, Busch proposed acquiring the remaining 50% it did not own of [[Grupo Modelo]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  InBev then said it would not include Busch in the new company board, but would include his uncle Adolphus Busch IV, who had favored the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=149574 |title=Adolphus Busch IV Responds as InBev Courts A-B Stockholders &#124; ksdk.com &#124; St. Louis, MO |publisher=ksdk.com |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> Eventually InBev sweetened its bid to $70 per share and kept Busch on the board.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/07/11/inbev-anheuser-talks-update-markets-equity-cx_je_0711markets11.html |title=InBev Seen Sweetening On Anheuser |publisher=Forbes.com |date= July 11, 2008|accessdate=December 27, 2010 |first=Javier |last=Espinoza}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 2008, he signed off on the sale of A-B to [[InBev]], ending 156 years of family control.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121608697120353241?mod=todays_us_marketplace | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Anheuser Deal Recognizes Its Tough Spot | date=July 15, 2008 | first1=David | last1=Kesmodel | first2=Dana | last2=Cimilluca | first3=Dennis | last3=Berman}}</ref>\n\nPress reports indicated that the Busch family ownership of the company had greatly dwindled over the years, with Busch's father owning 1.2 percent at the time of the takeover.  In total, the Busch family owned 4 percent of the company<ref name=\"adage1\">{{cite web|last=Arndorfer |first=James B. |url=http://adage.com/article?article_id=103802 |title=IS HE BUSCH LEAGUE?|publisher=Advertising Age |date=June 27, 2005 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> and were not the company's biggest shareholders.  [[Barclay's]] owned 6 percent and [[Berkshire Hathaway]] owned 5 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://todaysadvisor.com/InBev_Bud.aspx |title=InBev Bud |publisher=Todaysadvisor.com |date=May 23, 2008 |accessdate=December 28, 2010}}</ref>  The family did not own [[supervoting]] stock, as do many publicly traded companies with family affiliations. The board did not employ the common takeover defense tactic of staggering its board of directors terms (the A-B board was re-elected each year).{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nAccording to reports, Busch and his father were estranged. His father was said to have engineered the A-B takeover blindsiding the son. The public conflict between father and son led to the higher price.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> A-B gave Busch a title of non-executive director and a contract as a consultant that ran until December 2013.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} He was also given a security detail through 2011.<ref name=\"stltoday1\">{{cite web|author=Todd C. Frankel |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_2efd8b6d-b179-53dc-a6b9-dc9ae1c4e929.html |title=For Busch family, woman's death is latest in tragic history |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=October 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 26, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141940/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_2efd8b6d-b179-53dc-a6b9-dc9ae1c4e929.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe deal was worth $100 million to Busch.<ref name=\"stltoday2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_44d6e75c-a2ea-5bb7-94da-ea131ca86d46.html |title=Busch IV talks about death of girlfriend, his depression |publisher=Stltoday.com |accessdate=January 4, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141927/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_44d6e75c-a2ea-5bb7-94da-ea131ca86d46.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He also received a seat on InBev's board for a three-year term, $10.35 million in advance, and the promise of $120,000 a month in consultancy fees, as well as a personal security team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wydaily.com/business/2651-where-did-august-busch-iv-go.html |title=Where Did August Busch IV Go? |publisher=Wydaily.com |date=September 3, 2009 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> The same month the InBev takeover was completed, Busch resigned as a director of [[FedEx Corp]], a position he had held since 2003.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:August Busch IV in pilot suit.jpg|thumb|August Busch IV in flight suit]]\nBusch holds advanced [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] degrees in the [[martial arts]] disciplines of [[Judo]], [[Tae-Kwon-Do]], and [[Hapkido]]. He studied under Korean Grand Master Bong Yul Shin, who served as Busch's bodyguard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/print-edition/2011/03/04/st-louis-works-out-shin-builds.html|title=t. Louis Works Out: Shin builds strong mind, body through martial arts|last=Solomont|first=E.B.|date=March 4, 2011|work=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Busch, reported as a lean 5-foot-10-inch man in 2005, was described as having a striking resemblance to his father.<ref name=\"adage1\" />\n\nBusch IV and his family have a long history in aviation. Busch is trained to fly both helicopters and jets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2006/november/pilot/aopa-action-(11)|title=AOPA Action|date=2006-05-11|website=www.aopa.org|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nBusch married Kathryn \"Kate\" Thatcher, sixteen years his junior, in August 2006 in [[Bradford, Vermont]]<ref name=\"riverfronttimes1\">{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/august_busch_iv_divorce_filings.php |title=She Was His Wife, But She Wasn't his \"Bud\" ... The August Busch IV Divorce Files \u2013 St. Louis News \u2013 Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=December 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228014148/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/august_busch_iv_divorce_filings.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> shortly before becoming CEO.  He filed for divorce on November 26, 2008; the same month the InBev takeover was completed.  The couple had a [[prenuptial agreement]], and the divorce moved quickly through the courts, becoming official at the end of January 2009.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|page=366|title=Dethroning the King, The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, an American Icon|author=Julie MacIntosh|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|date=2011|ISBN=1118202821}}</ref><ref name=\"riverfronttimes1\"/><ref>{{cite news | author=Deb Peterson | title=After marriage of A-B and InBev, Busch IV filed for divorce | url=http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/news/columnists.nsf/debpeterson/story/306550826A6CC9F88625754E0007E595?OpenDocument| work=St. Louis Post Dispatch | date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=February 1, 2009 }}</ref>  The couple had no children.\n\n== Charity ==\nBusch IV currently serves or has served on numerous charitable boards, including:\n\n[[BackStoppers|Backstoppers]], current director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://backstoppers.org/board-of-directors-2/|title=Board of Directors|website=The BackStoppers, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nAugust Busch IV Foundation, which supports grant funding for Barnes Jewish Hospital study of treatment resistant depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Conway|first=Charles R.|last2=George|first2=Mark S.|last3=Sackeim|first3=Harold A.|date=2017-01-01|title=Toward an Evidence-Based, Operational Definition of Treatment-Resistant Depression: When Enough Is Enough|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2569455|journal=JAMA Psychiatry|language=en|volume=74|issue=1|pages=9\u201310|doi=10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2016.2586|issn=2168-622X}}</ref>\n\nFormer board member of [[Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital]] in St. Louis.<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nFormer board member of [[National Urban League]].<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nHonored by the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] for contributions to sports television.<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nLifetime achievement award from Larry King Cardiac Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2005/02/20/no-late-winters-nap-here-its-party-time/b400dd5f-3bce-4a12-86db-e87d51d62c2c/|title=No Late Winter's Nap Here: It's Party Time|last=Groom|first=Robin|date=February 20, 2005|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2005/02/20/no-late-winters-nap-here-its-party-time/b400dd5f-3bce-4a12-86db-e87d51d62c2c/|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles==\n\n===Accident resulting in death of Michele Frederick (1983)===\nAt age 19, while attending the [[University of Arizona]], Busch was in an auto accident that resulted in the death of his passenger, 21-year-old Michele Frederick, a local model and waitress.<ref>{{cite news|last=[[CBS News]]|title=August Busch IV in Headlines After Model Death|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-201_162-7182142.html|accessdate=October 24, 2012|date=December 24, 2010}}</ref> According to witnesses, Busch had left a bar early one morning with Frederick.<ref name=knoedelseder/> The vehicle wrecked at a 25&nbsp;mph curve known for accidents.<ref name=knoedelseder/> The car flipped and Frederick flew through the sunroof and was probably killed instantly when the car rolled over her.<ref name=knoedelseder/> Busch left the scene of the accident without informing anyone.<ref name=knoedelseder/> When police arrived on the scene hours later, they found empty Bud Light cans scattered in and around the car, along with Busch's driver's license.<ref name=knoedelseder/> Deputies found Busch at his Tucson townhouse 4 miles (6&nbsp;km) away, with blood on his body, a sawed-off shotgun, and in a dazed condition exhibiting signs of [[amnesia]].<ref name=knoedelseder/> Busch was found to have suffered a skull fracture in the accident.<ref name=da/> After a lengthy investigation by the Pima County Sheriff's Department in July 1984, the Pima County District Attorney announced he was not charging Busch with any wrongdoing.<ref name=knoedelseder/><ref name=da>{{cite web|title=Pima County District Attorney|url=http://www.stltoday.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/6/1e/61ec15fe-0758-11e2-aa75-001a4bcf6878/5062231d46b46.pdf.pdf}}</ref> He said that while Busch appeared to have been speeding at 45&nbsp;mph, that was not sufficient for charges, and witnesses from the bar did not report that he appeared to be drinking excessively.<ref name=da/>\n\nAs part of regular procedure, police took blood and urine samples from Busch while he was in custody. These samples were to assess whether and how much he had been drinking at the time of the accident.<ref name=knoedelseder/> However, the hospital lost the urine sample, and the blood sample had been run through a centrifuge, rendering it useless.<ref name=knoedelseder/> No one in the staff could explain what had happened. Police investigator Ron Benson said he had never before seen samples mishandled by hospital staff.<ref name=knoedelseder>{{cite book |title=Bitter Brew: The Rise and Fall of Anheuser-Busch and America's Kings of Beer |author=[[William Knoedelseder]] |chapter=Ch 14: \"Warning Sign\" |year=2012 |publisher=HarperBusiness |isbn=978-0062009265}}</ref> \n\n===Car chase (1985)===\nBusch was arrested at the age of 20 in St. Louis after leading undercover police in an unmarked car on a chase with speeds reaching between 85 and 90&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"riverfronttimes2\">{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2010/12/the_women_of_august_busch_iv.php |title=The Women of August Busch IV (NSFW) - St. Louis News - Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=September 30, 2010 |accessdate=December 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228230634/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2010/12/the_women_of_august_busch_iv.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> on Kingshighway Boulevard in the Central West End of the city.  He was returning from visiting PT's Sports Cabaret, a [[strip bar]] in [[Sauget, Illinois]].<ref name=\"riverfronttimes2\"/> The officers ended the chase by shooting out the rear tire of Busch's car. Busch claimed he thought they were attempting to kidnap him.<ref name=ACFfHL/> The police accused him of trying to run over two officers with his [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]].  Busch was acquitted of assault by a [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] jury.<ref>{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/st_louis_has_its_playboy_back_august_busch_iv_divorced.php |title=St. Louis Has Its Playboy Back! - St. Louis News - Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=December 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228005954/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/st_louis_has_its_playboy_back_august_busch_iv_divorced.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Death of Adrienne Nicole Martin (2010)===\nOn Sunday December 19, 2010, Adrienne Nicole Martin, a 27-year-old divorcee and part-time waitress who had been dating Busch for about two years, was found dead at Busch's home in [[Huntleigh, Missouri]].<ref name=\"stltoday1\"/> Busch was in the house at the time and a household employee called [[9-1-1]] at 1:15&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_01749250-1137-11e0-b13c-00127992bc8b.html |author= Blythe Bernhard |title=It's \"dark back there:\" 911 call from Busch home |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=December 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"stltoday1\"/> Her mother said her daughter was happy with Busch,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_8eaa7e69-6fc2-5b32-8480-d01a1da34fdd.html|title=Busch girlfriend's mother doesn't blame him for death, she says}}</ref> and Adrienne Martin's obituary would describe Busch as \"the love of her life.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Jesse Bogan|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_3ca05be8-c62b-543f-a06c-8cfd6fe5c512.html |title=In memorial, Adrienne Martin is remembered as talented, devoted |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=December 31, 2010 |accessdate=January 4, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141931/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_3ca05be8-c62b-543f-a06c-8cfd6fe5c512.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial autopsy revealed no signs of trauma and was inconclusive as to cause of death. Martin's ex-husband Kevin J. Martin, a [[Cape Girardeau, Missouri]] osteopathic physician, said Martin suffered from [[Long QT syndrome]], a heart condition that could cause an unexpected sudden death, but he had not discussed this with authorities. Martin's mother said that Martin was taking [[Trazodone]] for sleep issues. Kevin Martin noted such use needs to be monitored by a physician.<ref name=\"stltoday2\"/>\n\nThe matter was investigated by [[Frontenac, Missouri]] police, who ordered toxicology tests.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pistor |first=Nick |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/3920399e-0ec0-11e0-b6d8-0017a4a78c22.html |title=Woman found dead in home of August Busch IV |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kesmodel |first=David |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704278404576037970995344208 |title=Woman Found Dead at Home of Former Anheuser-Busch CEO August Busch IV \u2013 WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date= December 24, 2010|accessdate=December 24, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101228225820/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704278404576037970995344208.html| archivedate= December 28, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> A toxicology report in February 2011 indicated Martin had [[cocaine]] and [[oxycodone]] in her system; pill bottles with her name were found containing each of these. She had no prescription for either. The St. Louis County Prosecutor confirmed that Martin had lethal levels of both oxycodone and cocaine in her system, and ruled she died of an accidental overdose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_17b8cd8d-d2a7-533b-a437-ff7698daaf31.html |title=Busch girlfriend died with cocaine, oxycodone in system, sources say |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> The report noted that Martin's physical condition showed she had been using cocaine for several months to a year.\n\nOn March 31, 2011, Adrienne's ex-husband Kevin Martin filed a [[wrongful death]] suit against Busch for negligence and on behalf of her son Blake Alexander Martin (born 2002). The case was to be handled in Cape Girardeau.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_627f696c-5bba-11e0-8947-00127992bc8b.html |title=Wrongful-death suit filed against August Busch IV in overdose death |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> Adrienne's mother announced she was hiring New York attorney [[John Q. Kelly]] (who previously represented [[Beth Holloway]] and the estate of [[Nicole Brown Simpson]]) to pursue the case, and also said she would seek custody of her grandson. She was concerned that a friendship between Adrienne's ex-husband and Busch would taint the civil case.<ref name=\"stltoday3\"/> On April 6, 2011, Adrienne's father George \"Larry\" Eby joined the suit, saying he had been deprived of the \"companionship, comfort, instruction, guidance, counsel and training of Adrienne Martin.\"<ref name=\"father\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/article_0d8915c6-621c-11e0-ae49-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Busch wrongful death suit challenged by overdosed woman's father |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Friends of the family noted Eby and Martin had been estranged during her adult years.<ref name=\"stltoday3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_290f370e-6a29-53db-913e-472b1de6fce3.html |title=Woman's family squabbles in suit against Busch |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"father\"/>\n\nOn April 20, 2011, the press reported that Busch had agreed to a $1.5 million settlement with Kevin Martin on behalf of his son.  The court would decide how much could be allocated to Adrienne's parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_99a90917-e577-5b4e-953c-215363f59893.html |title=Busch OKs $1.5 million payment to settle suit |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Helicopter Incident===\n\nOn July 10, 2017 Busch was arrested in Swansea, Illinois after police alleged he tried to fly a helicopter while intoxicated. According to Swansea police, officers were called around 8:15pm when Busch IV appeared to be trying to take off in his helicopter while intoxicated. He was twice administered a breathalyzer and twice blew a 0.000.<ref name=ksk1>http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/former-anheuser-busch-ceo-arrested-for-trying-to-fly-helicopter-while-intoxicated/455816400</ref>  He was taken to a local hospital for blood and urine samples after officers conducted field sobriety tests, most of which Busch IV passed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmov.com/story/35859844/helicopter-pilot-arrested-for-attempting-to-fly-while-intoxicated|title=August Busch IV taken into custody after helicopter lands in parking lot|author=Rachel Sudduth|date=July 11, 2017|website=[[KMOV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestreet.com/story/14223262/1/ex-anheuser-busch-ceo-august-busch-iv-arrested-for-flying-helicopter-intoxicated.html |title=Former Anheuser Busch CEO August Busch IV Arrested For Flying Helicopter Intoxicated |publisher=thestreet.com |date= |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Officers believed he may have been under the influence of prescription drugs.<ref name=ksk1/> Blood tests later came back clean, according to the St. Clair County State's Attorney.<ref>http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/august-busch-ivs-blood-test-comes-back-clean-after-july-arrest/480849754</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Peter Hernon & Terry Ganey, ''Under the Influence: The Unauthorized Story of the Anheuser-Busch Dynasty'',  Avon Books, 1992\n*{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm |title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR August Busch IV is rebellious, risk-taking--and (nearly) ready to rule the world's largest brewer |work=[[Fortune Magazine]] |agency=Money.cnn.com |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}\n*''[[Business Week]]''; November 11, 2002\n*''[[Forbes]]''; March 3, 2006\n*[[Julie Macintosh]], ''Dethroning the King: The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, An American Icon'', John Wiley & Sons, Inc, 2010 {{isbn|1118202821}}\n*[[William Knoedelseder]], ''Bitter Brew: The Rise and Fall of Anheuser-Busch and America's Kings of Beer'', HarperBusiness, 2012\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busch, August, Iv}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American drink industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Busch family|August]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:American brewers]]\n[[Category:People from Ballwin, Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 5th generation brewing magnate|other persons|Busch (surname)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = August Busch IV\n| image       = August A. Busch IV with Budweiser Clydesdale.jpg\n| caption     = Busch with a Budweiser Clydesdale in 2006\n| birth_name  = August Adolphus Busch IV\n| occupation  = Board member of [[Anheuser-Busch InBev]]<br/>Retired president and CEO, [[Anheuser-Busch|Anheuser-Busch Companies, Inc.]]<br/>Retired director, [[FedEx]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1964|6|15}}\n| birth_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]], U.S.\n| alma_mater  = [[Saint Louis University]]<br/>[[VLB Berlin]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| spouse      = Kathryn \"Kate\" Thatcher <small>(2006-2009) divorced</small>\n| parents     = [[August Busch III]] and Susan (Hornibrook) Busch\n}}\n\n'''August Adolphus Busch IV''' (born June 15, 1964) is an American businessman and former CEO of [[Anheuser-Busch]]. He was the last of the family to control the company, which was purchased in a hostile takeover in 2008 by [[InBev]]. Busch IV was known for his marketing leadership, where his history as head of the Anheuser-Busch marketing department garnered ten straight ''USA Today'' [[Super Bowl Ad Meter]] awards, as well as awards at [[Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]] and the [[Clio Awards|Grand Clio]].<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://emmyonline.com/sports_27th_busch_honors|title=BUSCH FAMILY TO BE HONORED FOR DECADES OF OUTSTANDING CONTRIBUTIONS TO SPORTS TELEVISION BY NATIONAL TELEVISION ACADEMY {{!}} The Emmy Awards - The National Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://admeter.usatoday.com/|title=Ad Meter|website=Ad Meter|language=en|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/close-up-newsmaker-august-busch-iv---man-yes-budweisers-whassup-august-busch-scoops-highest-advertisers-award-cannes/46935|title=CLOSE-UP: NEWSMAKER/AUGUST BUSCH IV - The man who said yes to Budweiser's 'whassup?'. August Busch scoops the highest advertiser's award at Cannes|website=www.campaignlive.co.uk|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> He also served as a director of shipping giant [[FedEx]].<ref>{{cite web |title=FedEx |url=http://www.fedex.com/us/investorrelations/financialinfo/2005annualreport/online/board.html |website=FedEx.com}}</ref> Busch has been involved in a number of legal incidents during his lifetime.<ref name=knoedelseder/>\n\n==Early life==\nHe is a great-great-grandson of [[Anheuser-Busch]] founder [[Adolphus Busch]], and a great-great-great-grandson of [[Eberhard Anheuser]] who originally purchased the brewery in 1860. He is the son of Susan (Hornibrook) and [[August Busch III]], the former chairman, president and CEO of the company.\n\nBusch's parents divorced when he was five, and he lived with his mother.  His time with his father was mostly spent at the brewery and their relationship was, for the most part, professional.<ref name=ACFfHL>Kosmodel, David, \"Anheuser CEO Fight for His Legacy,\" ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', A1, May 27, 2008</ref>\n\n===Education===\n\nBusch received a bachelor's degree in finance and later a master's degree in business administration from [[Saint Louis University]]. He later served on the university's board of trustees.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Oliver |first1=Garrett |title=The Oxford Companion to Beer |date=2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |pages=197 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ga4MYyZq-RMC&pg=PA197&lpg=PA197&dq=%22august+busch+iv%22+and+%22saint+Louis+university%22&source=bl&ots=qEVqXZOln3&sig=ACfU3U1PH24PEy41L0U00rv3DFoZEdCzFQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwid0sO_ldHkAhWDTt8KHUAKDiA4ChDoATAAegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=%22august%20busch%20iv%22%20and%20%22saint%20Louis%20university%22&f=false |accessdate=14 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn his early twenties, Busch earned a brewmaster's degree from Versuchs und Lehranstalt fur Brauerei, a brewing institute in Berlin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ludington |first1=Callaway |title=Bud Man |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1991-06-14-9102220836-story.html |accessdate=14 September 2019 |publisher=Chicago Tribune |date=June 14, 1991}}</ref>\n\n==Anheuser-Busch==\n\n===Early years===\nAfter graduation he followed the family tradition of starting at the bottom of [[Anheuser-Busch]]. He worked as a brewing apprentice in the Old Malt House as a union member of Brewers & Maltsters Local 6 in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], as an intern in the culture yeast center, and later as a foreman in packaging and shipping operations.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn 1989, he moved into marketing, working on the [[Bud Dry]] brand launch. Although the launch was considered a success, the product ultimately proved to be unsuccessful.\n\nBusch's father initially opposed the campaign; he later admitted \"I've lost the ability to understand the 21- to 30-year-olds the way I used to.\"<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm | work=CNN | title=Bud-Weis-Heir August Busch Iv Is Rebellious, Risk-Taking--And (Nearly) Ready To Rule The World's Largest Brewer | first=Patricia | last=Sellers | date=January 13, 1997}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Busch was named vice president of brand management. In 1996, he became vice president of marketing. Busch was promoted in 2000 to group vice president of marketing and wholesale operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beerandbrewing.com/dictionary/Cd92zGLNQp|title=Busch, August IV|last=|first=|date=|website=Craft Beer and Brewing Magazine|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Under his leadership, the company emphasized more creative and often humorous advertising. In an interview with Fortune magazine, he recounted a conversation with his father August Busch III, then the company's president and CEO, that Budweiser sales would grow only if the iconic brand's identity was reinvented. \"There was a culture weaved into the Budweiser brand... No one wanted to change it,\" Busch IV told the magazine.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm|title=Bud-Weis-Heir August Busch IV Is Rebellious, Risk-Taking--and (Nearly) Ready to Rule the World's Largest Brewer|last=Sellers|first=Patricia|date=January 13, 1997|work=Fortune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The new advertising campaigns launched by Busch IV cemented his reputation for marketing instincts. The Budweiser and Bud Light commercials won the [[USA Today Super Bowl Ad Meter]]\u00a0every year from 1999 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://admeter.usatoday.com/2019/01/23/all-time-greatest-super-bowl-commercials/|title=All 31 Super Bowl Ad Meter-winning commercials from 1989 to 2018|last=Siegel|first=Alan|date=January 23, 2019|website=USA Today's Ad Meter website|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Budweiser frogs, penguins, ants, lizards ===\nBusch IV focused the marketing department on humor, youth, animals, and tradition. He insisted to his father that his department could make splashy\u2014yet risky\u2014ads targeted at a younger demographic. That led to the creation of the [[Budweiser Frogs]] advertising campaign featuring puppet frogs chirping \"Bud\", \"Weis\", and \"Er\". Other campaigns overseen by Busch IV featured a friendly alligator, a sinister penguin with the catchphrase \"doobie doobie do\", partying ants, and a self-absorbed lizard named Louie. The ads, according to Fortune Magazine, helped Anheuser-Busch stock rise by 27% in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm|title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR AUGUST BUSCH IV IS REBELLIOUS, RISK-TAKING--AND (NEARLY) READY TO RULE THE WORLD'S LARGEST BREWER. - January 13, 1997|website=money.cnn.com|access-date=2019-12-27}}</ref> \u00a0By 1998, the company achieved its best sales year ever.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/21/business/media-business-advertising-anheuser-busch-after-its-best-sales-year-ever.html|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING; Anheuser-Busch, after its best sales year ever, is spending a record sum on this year's Super Bowl.|last=Elliott|first=Stuart|date=1999-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-27|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n===Chairman and InBev takeover===\n[[File:AugustWarren.png|thumb|Former Anheuser-Busch CEO August Busch IV (right) with Berkshire Hathaway Chairman Warren Buffett (left). 2006]]\nIn 2002, Busch (and other family members) were passed over when the company named [[Patrick Stokes (businessman)|Patrick Stokes]] as its first non-family president and CEO.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/patrick-t-stokes/4237 |title=Patrick T. Stokes Profile - Forbes.com |publisher=People.forbes.com |date= |accessdate=December 26, 2010}}</ref>  Busch's father had said that he owns 1% of the stock and that the \"board of directors calls the shots\" at the company.<ref>{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm |title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR AUGUST BUSCH IV IS REBELLIOUS, RISK-TAKING-AND (NEARLY) READY TO RULE THE WORLD'S LARGEST BREWER.|publisher=Money.cnn.com |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=December 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, as president of the company, Busch IV announced the brewer had purchased the 20-year naming rights to a new [[Busch Stadium]], the home of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]. Team owner William Dewitt Jr. said: \u201cFrom the day we began planning for the new ballpark, we wanted to keep the name \u2018Busch Stadium.' August Busch IV and Anheuser-Busch share our vision for continuing that tradition for our great fans and the entire St. Louis community.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040805220653/http://www.anheuser-busch.com/news/BuschStadium_080404.htm|title=The Tradition Continues: St. Louis Cardinals to Play in Third 'Busch Stadium'|last=|first=|date=2004-08-05|website=www.anheuser-busch.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref> Dewitt, as part of an ownership group, had purchased the team from the brewery in 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/23/sports/busch-to-sell-cardinals.html|title=Busch to Sell Cardinals|last=|first=|date=1995-12-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBusch became president and CEO effective December 2006. Busch's father had been criticized for not expanding globally and leaving the company open for acquisition.  In 2007, August and the directors began discussions to acquire [[Diageo]] but the deal never advanced.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news|last=Kesmodel |first=David |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/deals/2010/09/29/new-book-says-busch-family-lost-budweiser-amid-infighting-missed-deals/ |title=New Book Says Busch Family Lost Budweiser Amid Infighting, Missed Deals - Deal Journal - WSJ |publisher=Blogs.wsj.com |date=September 29, 2010 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLess than 18 months into Busch's tenure, rumors circulated that [[InBev]] was attempting to buy the company.  In April 2008, Busch told beer distributors that Anheuser-Busch would never be bought \"on my watch.\"  A-B stock had closed at $49.20 on April 30, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=63607&p=irol-stocklookup |title=Anheuser-Busch Companies - Historical Price Lookup |publisher=Phx.corporate-ir.net |date=March 26, 1996 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref>  InBev offered $65 per share in June, and Busch refused.  Prior to InBev's offer, A-B's stock had never been higher than $51.97.  In hopes of keeping its independence, Busch proposed acquiring the remaining 50% it did not own of [[Grupo Modelo]].<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/>  InBev then said it would not include Busch in the new company board, but would include his uncle Adolphus Busch IV, who had favored the deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=149574 |title=Adolphus Busch IV Responds as InBev Courts A-B Stockholders &#124; ksdk.com &#124; St. Louis, MO |publisher=ksdk.com |date= |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> Eventually InBev sweetened its bid to $70 per share and kept Busch on the board.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/07/11/inbev-anheuser-talks-update-markets-equity-cx_je_0711markets11.html |title=InBev Seen Sweetening On Anheuser |publisher=Forbes.com |date= July 11, 2008|accessdate=December 27, 2010 |first=Javier |last=Espinoza}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 2008, he signed off on the sale of A-B to [[InBev]], ending 156 years of family control.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121608697120353241?mod=todays_us_marketplace | work=The Wall Street Journal | title=Anheuser Deal Recognizes Its Tough Spot | date=July 15, 2008 | first1=David | last1=Kesmodel | first2=Dana | last2=Cimilluca | first3=Dennis | last3=Berman}}</ref>\n\nPress reports indicated that the Busch family ownership of the company had greatly dwindled over the years, with Busch's father owning 1.2 percent at the time of the takeover.  In total, the Busch family owned 4 percent of the company<ref name=\"adage1\">{{cite web|last=Arndorfer |first=James B. |url=http://adage.com/article?article_id=103802 |title=IS HE BUSCH LEAGUE?|publisher=Advertising Age |date=June 27, 2005 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> and were not the company's biggest shareholders.  [[Barclay's]] owned 6 percent and [[Berkshire Hathaway]] owned 5 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://todaysadvisor.com/InBev_Bud.aspx |title=InBev Bud |publisher=Todaysadvisor.com |date=May 23, 2008 |accessdate=December 28, 2010}}</ref>  The family did not own [[supervoting]] stock, as do many publicly traded companies with family affiliations. The board did not employ the common takeover defense tactic of staggering its board of directors terms (the A-B board was re-elected each year).{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\nAccording to reports, Busch and his father were estranged. His father was said to have engineered the A-B takeover blindsiding the son. The public conflict between father and son led to the higher price.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> A-B gave Busch a title of non-executive director and a contract as a consultant that ran until December 2013.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} He was also given a security detail through 2011.<ref name=\"stltoday1\">{{cite web|author=Todd C. Frankel |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_2efd8b6d-b179-53dc-a6b9-dc9ae1c4e929.html |title=For Busch family, woman's death is latest in tragic history |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=October 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 26, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141940/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_2efd8b6d-b179-53dc-a6b9-dc9ae1c4e929.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe deal was worth $100 million to Busch.<ref name=\"stltoday2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_44d6e75c-a2ea-5bb7-94da-ea131ca86d46.html |title=Busch IV talks about death of girlfriend, his depression |publisher=Stltoday.com |accessdate=January 4, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141927/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_44d6e75c-a2ea-5bb7-94da-ea131ca86d46.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>  He also received a seat on InBev's board for a three-year term, $10.35 million in advance, and the promise of $120,000 a month in consultancy fees, as well as a personal security team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wydaily.com/business/2651-where-did-august-busch-iv-go.html |title=Where Did August Busch IV Go? |publisher=Wydaily.com |date=September 3, 2009 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref> The same month the InBev takeover was completed, Busch resigned as a director of [[FedEx Corp]], a position he had held since 2003.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:August Busch IV in pilot suit.jpg|thumb|August Busch IV in flight suit]]\nBusch holds advanced [[black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] degrees in the [[martial arts]] disciplines of [[Judo]], [[Tae-Kwon-Do]], and [[Hapkido]]. He studied under Korean Grand Master Bong Yul Shin, who served as Busch's bodyguard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/stlouis/print-edition/2011/03/04/st-louis-works-out-shin-builds.html|title=t. Louis Works Out: Shin builds strong mind, body through martial arts|last=Solomont|first=E.B.|date=March 4, 2011|work=St. Louis Business Journal|access-date=December 16, 2019}}</ref> Busch, reported as a lean 5-foot-10-inch man in 2005, was described as having a striking resemblance to his father.<ref name=\"adage1\" />\n\nBusch IV and his family have a long history in aviation. Busch is trained to fly both helicopters and jets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aopa.org/news-and-media/all-news/2006/november/pilot/aopa-action-(11)|title=AOPA Action|date=2006-05-11|website=www.aopa.org|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\nBusch married Kathryn \"Kate\" Thatcher, sixteen years his junior, in August 2006 in [[Bradford, Vermont]]<ref name=\"riverfronttimes1\">{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/august_busch_iv_divorce_filings.php |title=She Was His Wife, But She Wasn't his \"Bud\" ... The August Busch IV Divorce Files \u2013 St. Louis News \u2013 Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=December 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228014148/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/august_busch_iv_divorce_filings.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> shortly before becoming CEO.  He filed for divorce on November 26, 2008; the same month the InBev takeover was completed.  The couple had a [[prenuptial agreement]], and the divorce moved quickly through the courts, becoming official at the end of January 2009.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite book|page=366|title=Dethroning the King, The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, an American Icon|author=Julie MacIntosh|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|date=2011|ISBN=1118202821}}</ref><ref name=\"riverfronttimes1\"/><ref>{{cite news | author=Deb Peterson | title=After marriage of A-B and InBev, Busch IV filed for divorce | url=http://www.stltoday.com/stltoday/news/columnists.nsf/debpeterson/story/306550826A6CC9F88625754E0007E595?OpenDocument| work=St. Louis Post Dispatch | date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=February 1, 2009 }}</ref>  The couple had no children.\n\n== Charity ==\nBusch IV currently serves or has served on numerous charitable boards, including:\n\n[[BackStoppers|Backstoppers]], current director.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://backstoppers.org/board-of-directors-2/|title=Board of Directors|website=The BackStoppers, Inc.|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref>\n\nAugust Busch IV Foundation, which supports grant funding for Barnes Jewish Hospital study of treatment resistant depression.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Conway|first=Charles R.|last2=George|first2=Mark S.|last3=Sackeim|first3=Harold A.|date=2017-01-01|title=Toward an Evidence-Based, Operational Definition of Treatment-Resistant Depression: When Enough Is Enough|url=https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamapsychiatry/fullarticle/2569455|journal=JAMA Psychiatry|language=en|volume=74|issue=1|pages=9\u201310|doi=10.1001/jamapsychiatry.2016.2586|issn=2168-622X}}</ref>\n\nFormer board member of [[Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital]] in St. Louis.<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nFormer board member of [[National Urban League]].<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nHonored by the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] for contributions to sports television.<ref name=\"emmyonline.com\"/>\n\nLifetime achievement award from Larry King Cardiac Foundation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2005/02/20/no-late-winters-nap-here-its-party-time/b400dd5f-3bce-4a12-86db-e87d51d62c2c/|title=No Late Winter's Nap Here: It's Party Time|last=Groom|first=Robin|date=February 20, 2005|website=Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2005/02/20/no-late-winters-nap-here-its-party-time/b400dd5f-3bce-4a12-86db-e87d51d62c2c/|archive-date=|access-date=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Legal troubles==\n\n===Accident resulting in death of Michele Frederick (1983)===\nAt age 19, while attending the [[University of Arizona]], Busch was in an auto accident that resulted in the death of his passenger, 21-year-old Michele Frederick, a local model and waitress.<ref>{{cite news|last=[[CBS News]]|title=August Busch IV in Headlines After Model Death|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/2100-201_162-7182142.html|accessdate=October 24, 2012|date=December 24, 2010}}</ref> According to witnesses, Busch had left a bar early one morning with Frederick.<ref name=knoedelseder/> The vehicle wrecked at a 25&nbsp;mph curve known for accidents.<ref name=knoedelseder/> The car flipped and Frederick flew through the sunroof and was probably killed instantly when the car rolled over her.<ref name=knoedelseder/> Busch left the scene of the accident without informing anyone.<ref name=knoedelseder/> When police arrived on the scene hours later, they found empty Bud Light cans scattered in and around the car, along with Busch's driver's license.<ref name=knoedelseder/> Deputies found Busch at his Tucson townhouse 4 miles (6&nbsp;km) away, with blood on his body, a sawed-off shotgun, and in a dazed condition exhibiting signs of [[amnesia]].<ref name=knoedelseder/> Busch was found to have suffered a skull fracture in the accident.<ref name=da/> After a lengthy investigation by the Pima County Sheriff's Department in July 1984, the Pima County District Attorney announced he was not charging Busch with any wrongdoing.<ref name=knoedelseder/><ref name=da>{{cite web|title=Pima County District Attorney|url=http://www.stltoday.com/content/tncms/assets/v3/editorial/6/1e/61ec15fe-0758-11e2-aa75-001a4bcf6878/5062231d46b46.pdf.pdf}}</ref> He said that while Busch appeared to have been speeding at 45&nbsp;mph, that was not sufficient for charges, and witnesses from the bar did not report that he appeared to be drinking excessively.<ref name=da/>\n\nAs part of regular procedure, police took blood and urine samples from Busch while he was in custody. These samples were to assess whether and how much he had been drinking at the time of the accident.<ref name=knoedelseder/> However, the hospital lost the urine sample, and the blood sample had been run through a centrifuge, rendering it useless.<ref name=knoedelseder/> No one in the staff could explain what had happened. Police investigator Ron Benson said he had never before seen samples mishandled by hospital staff.<ref name=knoedelseder>{{cite book |title=Bitter Brew: The Rise and Fall of Anheuser-Busch and America's Kings of Beer |author=[[William Knoedelseder]] |chapter=Ch 14: \"Warning Sign\" |year=2012 |publisher=HarperBusiness |isbn=978-0062009265}}</ref> Years later Benson said, \"I didn't feel good about [dropping the case]. My gut told me this guy was drunk and killed this girl and I couldn't do my best for her because the [blood and urine] evidence just disappeared.\"<ref name=knoedelseder/>\n\n[[William Knoedelseder]], who wrote a biography of the Busch family, speculated that Busch attorneys likely made a private, secret settlement with the Frederick family.<ref name=knoedelseder/> August IV's mother, Susie Busch, wrote in a newspaper column that her son had not been treated justly:  \"there is no just treatment for families with a name and money.\"<ref name=knoedelseder/>\n\n===Car chase (1985)===\nBusch was arrested at the age of 20 in St. Louis after leading undercover police in an unmarked car on a chase with speeds reaching between 85 and 90&nbsp;mph.<ref name=\"riverfronttimes2\">{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2010/12/the_women_of_august_busch_iv.php |title=The Women of August Busch IV (NSFW) - St. Louis News - Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=September 30, 2010 |accessdate=December 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228230634/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2010/12/the_women_of_august_busch_iv.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> on Kingshighway Boulevard in the Central West End of the city.  He was returning from visiting PT's Sports Cabaret, a [[strip bar]] in [[Sauget, Illinois]].<ref name=\"riverfronttimes2\"/> The officers ended the chase by shooting out the rear tire of Busch's car. Busch claimed he thought they were attempting to kidnap him.<ref name=ACFfHL/> The police accused him of trying to run over two officers with his [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]].  Busch was acquitted of assault by a [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]] jury.<ref>{{cite web |last=Garrison |first=Chad |url=http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/st_louis_has_its_playboy_back_august_busch_iv_divorced.php |title=St. Louis Has Its Playboy Back! - St. Louis News - Daily RFT |publisher=Blogs.riverfronttimes.com |date=January 30, 2009 |accessdate=December 26, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228005954/http://blogs.riverfronttimes.com/dailyrft/2009/01/st_louis_has_its_playboy_back_august_busch_iv_divorced.php |archive-date=December 28, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Death of Adrienne Nicole Martin (2010)===\nOn Sunday December 19, 2010, Adrienne Nicole Martin, a 27-year-old divorcee and part-time waitress who had been dating Busch for about two years, was found dead at Busch's home in [[Huntleigh, Missouri]].<ref name=\"stltoday1\"/> Busch was in the house at the time and a household employee called [[9-1-1]] at 1:15&nbsp;p.m.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_01749250-1137-11e0-b13c-00127992bc8b.html |author= Blythe Bernhard |title=It's \"dark back there:\" 911 call from Busch home |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=December 27, 2010 |accessdate=December 27, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"stltoday1\"/> Her mother said her daughter was happy with Busch,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_8eaa7e69-6fc2-5b32-8480-d01a1da34fdd.html|title=Busch girlfriend's mother doesn't blame him for death, she says}}</ref> and Adrienne Martin's obituary would describe Busch as \"the love of her life.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Jesse Bogan|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_3ca05be8-c62b-543f-a06c-8cfd6fe5c512.html |title=In memorial, Adrienne Martin is remembered as talented, devoted |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=December 31, 2010 |accessdate=January 4, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110204141931/http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/article_3ca05be8-c62b-543f-a06c-8cfd6fe5c512.html| archivedate= February 4, 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nThe initial autopsy revealed no signs of trauma and was inconclusive as to cause of death. Martin's ex-husband Kevin J. Martin, a [[Cape Girardeau, Missouri]] osteopathic physician, said Martin suffered from [[Long QT syndrome]], a heart condition that could cause an unexpected sudden death, but he had not discussed this with authorities. Martin's mother said that Martin was taking [[Trazodone]] for sleep issues. Kevin Martin noted such use needs to be monitored by a physician.<ref name=\"stltoday2\"/>\n\nThe matter was investigated by [[Frontenac, Missouri]] police, who ordered toxicology tests.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pistor |first=Nick |url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/metro/3920399e-0ec0-11e0-b6d8-0017a4a78c22.html |title=Woman found dead in home of August Busch IV |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Kesmodel |first=David |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704278404576037970995344208 |title=Woman Found Dead at Home of Former Anheuser-Busch CEO August Busch IV \u2013 WSJ.com |publisher=Online.wsj.com |date= December 24, 2010|accessdate=December 24, 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101228225820/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704278404576037970995344208.html| archivedate= December 28, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> A toxicology report in February 2011 indicated Martin had [[cocaine]] and [[oxycodone]] in her system; pill bottles with her name were found containing each of these. She had no prescription for either. The St. Louis County Prosecutor confirmed that Martin had lethal levels of both oxycodone and cocaine in her system, and ruled she died of an accidental overdose.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_17b8cd8d-d2a7-533b-a437-ff7698daaf31.html |title=Busch girlfriend died with cocaine, oxycodone in system, sources say |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> The report noted that Martin's physical condition showed she had been using cocaine for several months to a year.\n\nOn March 31, 2011, Adrienne's ex-husband Kevin Martin filed a [[wrongful death]] suit against Busch for negligence and on behalf of her son Blake Alexander Martin (born 2002). The case was to be handled in Cape Girardeau.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_627f696c-5bba-11e0-8947-00127992bc8b.html |title=Wrongful-death suit filed against August Busch IV in overdose death |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> Adrienne's mother announced she was hiring New York attorney [[John Q. Kelly]] (who previously represented [[Beth Holloway]] and the estate of [[Nicole Brown Simpson]]) to pursue the case, and also said she would seek custody of her grandson. She was concerned that a friendship between Adrienne's ex-husband and Busch would taint the civil case.<ref name=\"stltoday3\"/> On April 6, 2011, Adrienne's father George \"Larry\" Eby joined the suit, saying he had been deprived of the \"companionship, comfort, instruction, guidance, counsel and training of Adrienne Martin.\"<ref name=\"father\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/article_0d8915c6-621c-11e0-ae49-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Busch wrongful death suit challenged by overdosed woman's father |publisher=Stltoday.com |date=April 8, 2011 |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref> Friends of the family noted Eby and Martin had been estranged during her adult years.<ref name=\"stltoday3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_290f370e-6a29-53db-913e-472b1de6fce3.html |title=Woman's family squabbles in suit against Busch |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"father\"/>\n\nOn April 20, 2011, the press reported that Busch had agreed to a $1.5 million settlement with Kevin Martin on behalf of his son.  The court would decide how much could be allocated to Adrienne's parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/article_99a90917-e577-5b4e-953c-215363f59893.html |title=Busch OKs $1.5 million payment to settle suit |publisher=Stltoday.com |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Helicopter Incident===\n\nOn July 10, 2017 Busch was arrested in Swansea, Illinois after police alleged he tried to fly a helicopter while intoxicated. According to Swansea police, officers were called around 8:15pm when Busch IV appeared to be trying to take off in his helicopter while intoxicated. He was twice administered a breathalyzer and twice blew a 0.000.<ref name=ksk1>http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/former-anheuser-busch-ceo-arrested-for-trying-to-fly-helicopter-while-intoxicated/455816400</ref>  He was taken to a local hospital for blood and urine samples after officers conducted field sobriety tests, most of which Busch IV passed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kmov.com/story/35859844/helicopter-pilot-arrested-for-attempting-to-fly-while-intoxicated|title=August Busch IV taken into custody after helicopter lands in parking lot|author=Rachel Sudduth|date=July 11, 2017|website=[[KMOV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestreet.com/story/14223262/1/ex-anheuser-busch-ceo-august-busch-iv-arrested-for-flying-helicopter-intoxicated.html |title=Former Anheuser Busch CEO August Busch IV Arrested For Flying Helicopter Intoxicated |publisher=thestreet.com |date= |accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Officers believed he may have been under the influence of prescription drugs.<ref name=ksk1/> Blood tests later came back clean, according to the St. Clair County State's Attorney.<ref>http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/august-busch-ivs-blood-test-comes-back-clean-after-july-arrest/480849754</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Peter Hernon & Terry Ganey, ''Under the Influence: The Unauthorized Story of the Anheuser-Busch Dynasty'',  Avon Books, 1992\n*{{cite news|last=Sellers |first=Patricia |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/1997/01/13/220882/index.htm |title=BUD-WEIS-HEIR August Busch IV is rebellious, risk-taking--and (nearly) ready to rule the world's largest brewer |work=[[Fortune Magazine]] |agency=Money.cnn.com |date=January 13, 1997 |accessdate=December 24, 2010}}\n*''[[Business Week]]''; November 11, 2002\n*''[[Forbes]]''; March 3, 2006\n*[[Julie Macintosh]], ''Dethroning the King: The Hostile Takeover of Anheuser-Busch, An American Icon'', John Wiley & Sons, Inc, 2010 {{isbn|1118202821}}\n*[[William Knoedelseder]], ''Bitter Brew: The Rise and Fall of Anheuser-Busch and America's Kings of Beer'', HarperBusiness, 2012\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Anheuser-Busch InBev}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Busch, August, Iv}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American drink industry businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Busch family|August]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis University alumni]]\n[[Category:Missouri Democrats]]\n[[Category:American brewers]]\n[[Category:People from Ballwin, Missouri]]